# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alois-mertes
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alois-mertes/alois-mertes] After graduating from the Regino Gymnasium in Prüm in 1940, Mertes took part in World War II as a soldier.
[src:alois-mertes/alois-mertes] After his release from captivity, Mertes studied law, history and Romance languages and literature at the universities of Bonn and Paris.
[src:alois-mertes/alois-mertes] In 1948, he graduated with a state examination in history and French and received his doctorate in 1951 from the University of Bonn with a thesis entitled *France's Opinion on the German Revolution in 1848*.
[src:alois-mertes/alois-mertes] In 1952 Mertes entered the diplomatic service of the Federal Republic of Germany, for which he worked at the Consulate General in Marseille and at the embassies in Paris (1958–1963) and Moscow (1963–1966).
[src:alois-mertes/alois-mertes] He completed a study visit in 1968/69 at the Center for International Affairs at Harvard University, directed by Henry Kissinger, with the study *Reflections on Détente: Russia, Germany, and the West*.
[src:alois-mertes/alois-mertes] After his return to Bonn, he took over the Department of European Security and Regional Disarmament at the Federal Foreign Office.
[src:alois-mertes/alois-mertes] From 1969 to 1971, he was chairman of the Catholic League of New Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/alois-mertes] From 1969 to 1972, he held a lectureship in political science at the University of Cologne.
[src:alois-mertes/alois-mertes] In 1972, Mertes was state secretary and plenipotentiary of the State of Rhineland-Palatinate to the Federal Government.
[src:alois-mertes/alois-mertes] From 1972 until his death, he was a member of the German Bundestag.
[src:alois-mertes/alois-mertes] Mertes always entered the Bundestag as a directly elected member of parliament for the constituency of Bitburg.
[src:alois-mertes/alois-mertes] Here he was chairman of the foreign policy working group of the CDU/CSU parliamentary group from 1980 to 1982.
[src:alois-mertes/alois-mertes] As member of the Bundstag he advocated for the release of German war convicts held in Western European captivity, such as Herbert Kappler in Italy and the Breda Two in the Netherlands.
[src:alois-mertes/alois-mertes] On 4 October 1982, he was appointed Minister of State at the Foreign Office in the federal government led by Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
[src:alois-mertes/alois-mertes] Mertes was married to Hiltrud Mertes née Becker since 1951.
[src:alois-mertes/alois-mertes] The marriage produced five children, including Michael Mertes and the Jesuit Klaus Mertes.
[src:alois-mertes/alois-mertes] Mertes died four days after suffering a severe stroke during a panel discussion.
[src:alois-mertes/alois-mertes] In a series of eight "Alois Mertes Memorial Lectures" (1991–1999), the German Historical Institute in Washington had Mertes's many conceptual contributions to German foreign and security policy honored by renowned scholars of history, politics, and the humanities.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] The city's name derives from its Celtic toponym, *Beda*.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] Bitburg originated approximately 2,000 years ago as a stopover for traffic from Lyon through Metz and Trier to Cologne.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] The first name mentioned was *Vicus Beda*.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] Emperor Constantine the Great expanded the settlement to a road castle around 330, the central part of which forms the town centre today.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] Bitburg is first documented only after the end of the Roman Empire around 715 as *castrum bedense*.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] It subsequently became part of Franconia.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] The first mention of Bitburg in historic annals occurred in connection with the signing in 1239 of the Trier-Luxembourg Treaty between Archbishop Theoderich II of Trier and Countess Ermesinde II of Luxemburg, under which the town came under the archbishopric's protection.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] Bitburg received a town charter in 1262 from Count Henry V of Luxembourg.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] In 1443, Bitburg came under the sway of the Duchy of Burgundy, then in 1506 was acquired by the Austrian Netherlands, which controlled most of modern Belgium.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] In 1794 the city came under French administration, and in 1798 became part of the newly created *Département des Forêts*.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] This led to a short lived economic upturn, and Bitburg received among other things a court and a land registry.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] With the unification of Germany under Prussian dominance in 1871, Bitburg became part of the German Empire, and after World War I the Weimar Republic of Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] In the interwar years, Bitburg, like most of the Eifel region, was impoverished and comparatively backward.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] Economic growth began after the Nazi Seizure of Power and the Nazi regime's introduction of employment-boosting public works projects, including infrastructure for war, particularly the Westwall; new armed forces barracks; and the development of the Nims-Sauer Valley railway.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] It is said that the building now used as the post office at Bitburg Annex (what is left of Bitburg Air Base) was the headquarters for Adolf Hitler when he was in the city.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] In late December 1944, Bitburg was 85 percent destroyed by Allied bombing attacks, and later officially designated by the U.S. military as a "dead city." Subsequently, the town was occupied by Luxembourg soldiers, who were replaced by French forces in 1955.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] In 1952 a North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) base was opened at Bitburg by the U.S.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] At the end of the 1980s, French troops were withdrawn and NATO took over the former French barracks.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] After the First Gulf War most of the USAF forces were moved to the larger Spangdahlem Air Base, about 12 km east of Bitburg.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] In 1994, NATO turned the Bitburg Air Base over to the city, which devoted it to public works projects.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] The Nims-Sauer Valley railway was abandoned step by step, beginning in 1969.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] Parts of it were converted into a bicycle path (*Radweg*).
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] In 1985, Bitburg came to international attention due to a ceremonial visit by U.S.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] President Ronald Reagan and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl to the nearby Kolmeshöhe Military Cemetery – which among its 2,000 graves included those of 49 members of the Waffen-SS.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] The most widely known Bitburg enterprise, and landmark of the city, is the Bitburger brewery.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] 3 among Germany's best selling beers, with sales of 3.86 million hectolitres (in 2008).
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] In 1995, the former NATO base was designated the **Bitburg Airfield Trade Area**, providing commercial development district where 180 enterprises have established themselves.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] Bitburg-Erdorf station is part of the Eifel line (KBS 474).
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] The nearest airports are Luxembourg Airport (61 km away) and Hahn Airport (79 km away).
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] The Regional Museum of Bitburg-Prüm is housed in a former agricultural school.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] It contains numerous artifacts of the history of Bitburg and the Eifel Region in general.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] In the cultural centre *Haus Beda* are exhibited works of the Düsseldorf painter Fritz von Wille (1860–1941), the Eifel's most widely known artist.
[src:alois-mertes/bitburg] More than 100 paintings are on display, including *Die blaue Blume*, *Mosenberg*, *Burg Reifferscheid im Winter* and *Ein klarer Tag*.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Bonn served as the capital of West Germany from 1949 until 1990 and was the seat of government for reunified Germany until 1999, when the government relocated to Berlin.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The city holds historical significance as the birthplace of Germany's current constitution, the Basic Law.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Founded in the 1st century BC as a settlement of the Ubii and later part of the Roman province Germania Inferior, Bonn is among Germany's oldest cities.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] It was the capital city of the Electorate of Cologne from 1597 to 1794 and served as the residence of the Archbishops and Prince-electors of Cologne.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The period during which Bonn was the capital of West Germany is often referred to by historians as the *Bonn Republic*.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Following the German reunification, a political compromise known as the Berlin-Bonn Act ensured that the German federal government retained a significant presence in Bonn.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] As of 2019, approximately one-third of all ministerial jobs remain in the city.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Bonn is considered an unofficial secondary capital of Germany and is the location of the secondary seats of the president, the chancellor, and the Bundesrat.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Bonn is also the location of the primary seats of six federal ministries and twenty federal authorities.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The city's title as Federal City (German: *Bundesstadt*) underscores its political importance.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The global headquarters of Deutsche Post DHL and Deutsche Telekom, both DAX-listed corporations, are in Bonn.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The city is home to the Rheinische Friedrich-Wilhelms-Universität Bonn university, and a total of 20 United Nations institutions, the highest number in all of Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] These institutions include the headquarters for Secretariat of the UN Framework Convention Climate Change (UNFCCC), the Secretariat of the UN Convention to Combat Desertification (UNCCD), and the UN Volunteers programme.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Birthplace of composer Ludwig van Beethoven, a center of Rhenish carnival, and its geography by the Middle Rhine make it an important tourist destination.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] In Bonn the Bönnsch Platt, a dialect of the Ripuarian language is spoken by all generations, especially during carnival.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Situated in the southernmost part of the Rhine-Ruhr region, Germany's largest metropolitan area with over 11 million inhabitants, Bonn lies within the German state of North Rhine-Westphalia, on the border with Rhineland-Palatinate.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Spanning an area of more 141.2 km2 (55 sq mi) on both sides of the river Rhine, almost three-quarters of the city lies on the river's left bank.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] To the south and to the west, Bonn borders the Eifel region which encompasses the Rhineland Nature Park.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] To the north, Bonn borders the Cologne Lowland.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Natural borders are constituted by the river Sieg to the north-east and by the Siebengebirge (also known as the Seven Hills) to the east.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The largest extension of the city in north–south dimensions is 15 km (9 mi) and 12.5 km (8 mi) in west–east dimensions.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The city borders have a total length of 61 km (38 mi).
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The geographical centre of Bonn is the Bundeskanzlerplatz *(Chancellor Square)* in Bonn-Gronau.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The German state of North Rhine-Westphalia is divided into five governmental districts (German: *Regierungsbezirk*), and Bonn is part of the governmental district of Cologne (German: *Regierungsbezirk Köln*).
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Within this governmental district, the city of Bonn is an urban district in its own right.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The urban district of Bonn is then again divided into four administrative municipal districts (German: *Stadtbezirk*).
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] These are Bonn, Bonn-Bad Godesberg, Bonn-Beuel and Bonn-Hardtberg.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] In 1969, the independent towns of Bad Godesberg and Beuel as well as several villages were incorporated into Bonn, resulting in a city more than twice as large as before.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Bonn has an oceanic climate (Köppen: *Cfb*; Trewartha: *Dobk*).
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] In the south of the Cologne lowland in the Rhine valley, Bonn is in one of Germany's warmest regions.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] In 1989, Bonn celebrated its 2,000th anniversary.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The city was commemorating the construction of the first fortified Roman camp on the Rhine in 12 BCE, after the Roman governor Agrippa had already settled the Ubii there in 38 BCE.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] However, people had lived in the area of today's city much earlier.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Evidence of this includes the 14,000-year-old double burial at Oberkassel as well as a trench and wooden palisades found on the Venusberg, dating back to around 4080 BCE.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] In the years before the birth of Christ, Roman presence in Bonna was modest, but this changed after the Roman defeat in the Battle of the Teutoburg Forest in 9 CE.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] In the following decades, a legion was stationed there, which built the Legionary Fortress Bonn in the northern part of present-day Bonn.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Around the camp, and to the south along what is now Adenauerallee, traders and craftsmen settled in a vicus.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] With the end of the Roman Empire, Bonn declined during Late Antiquity and the Early Middle Ages.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] During the Viking raids in the Rhineland, Bonn was burned twice in 882, and in 883, the recently rebuilt town was again attacked, burned, and looted by the Normans.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] In the Frankish Empire, and finally in the 9th and 10th centuries, a religious center developed around the Bonn Minster (the Villa Basilika), and a market settlement emerged in the area of today's market square.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The year 1243 is considered the year in which Bonn was granted full city rights.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The outcome of the Battle of Worringen in 1288 was of great importance for the further development of the city.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The Cologne prince-electors made Bonn—along with Brühl and Poppelsdorf—one of their residences, and eventually their residence city.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The magnificent palaces built by the prince-electors in the 17th and 18th centuries gave the city its baroque splendor.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] This era ended with the occupation by French troops on October 8, 1794.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] This was followed by nearly two decades of occupation by the troops of Napoleon.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Taxes in the form of food, clothing, and accommodations, as well as the loss of the electoral state administration, led to poverty among the population and a decline in the number of inhabitants by around 20%.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The French introduced a civil code (Code civil) and a municipal constitution in Bonn.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Even under French occupation, medium and large industrial companies, particularly in the textile sector, were established in Bonn.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The French also pursued a thorough secularization: properties of the ecclesiastical electorate, especially the electoral buildings, were taken into state ownership.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The areas on the right bank of the Rhine that are now part of Bonn (Vilich) came into the possession of the Prince of Nassau-Usingen; Oberkassel belonged to the Duchy of Berg, a French satellite state.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] By the Treaty of Lunéville of February 9, 1801, the Rhine near Bonn was designated as the French eastern border.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Bonn became the seat of a sub-prefecture in the newly formed Rhin-et-Moselle.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] After the defeats of the French army in the Russian campaign of 1812 and the Battle of Leipzig, the French evacuated Bonn in January 1814.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Following the decisions of the Congress of Vienna, Bonn became part of Prussia in 1815.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] In the following decades, the city was shaped by the newly founded University of Bonn, established by the Prussian government on October 18, 1818.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The founder and namesake was King Frederick William III of Prussia.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] A university had existed in Bonn at the end of the 18th century but was closed during the French occupation in 1794.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The Prussian foundation was not a continuation of that earlier institution, but part of a program that also included the University of Berlin and the University of Breslau.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The term Rheinische in the name of the Bonn university was meant to mark it as a "sister" institution to the Berlin and Breslau universities.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Over the next 100 years, Bonn became the preferred place of study for the Hohenzollern princes.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] It was nicknamed the "Princes' University," as both the then-Prussian Crown Prince Frederick William, his son Wilhelm, and Wilhelm's four sons studied there.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Other sons of noble families also favored studying at this university in the 19th century.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Before the founding of the Bonn university, Cologne had been its main rival.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The "enlightened tradition" of Bonn, compared to the "holy Cologne," likely made it more suitable for a confessionally neutral university.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Practical reasons also favored Bonn: the old electoral palace and the Poppelsdorf Palace were already available as suitable buildings.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] From 1815 onward, professors, students, civil servants, and officers arrived in Bonn, including many Protestants from the Prussian provinces, which was unusual for the predominantly Catholic Rhineland.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] As a result, Bonn became popular as a retirement location for military officers.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Tourism also grew after German unification in 1871, fueled by the Romanticism on the Rhine of the time.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] After the First World War, the city was initially occupied by Canadian, then British, and finally (until 1926) by French troops.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] More than 1,000 Bonn residents, mostly of Jewish descent, were murdered during the Nazi era (Holocaust).
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] About 8,000 people were forced to leave their hometown, were arrested, or imprisoned in concentration camps.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] When American troops entered Bonn on March 9, 1945, ending World War II for the city, 30% of the buildings were destroyed.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Of these, 70% were slightly to severely damaged, and 30% were completely destroyed residential buildings.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] More than 4,000 Bonn residents had died in bombings.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] On May 28, 1945, Bonn became part of the British occupation zone.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] After the Second World War, the city experienced rapid reconstruction and expansion, especially after the decision to make Bonn the provisional capital of the new Federal Republic of Germany instead of Frankfurt am Main on November 29, 1949 (see Capital of Germany#The capital debate).
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] On October 30, 2014, under the patronage and active participation of Chancellor Angela Merkel, the Unity Tree Monument for German Unity was planted.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The city of Bonn was enlarged several times through municipal mergers.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] As a result, on June 1, 1904, the towns of Poppelsdorf, Endenich, Kessenich, and Dottendorf—which had already merged physically with Bonn—were incorporated.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Through the law on the municipal reorganization of the Bonn area ("Bonn Act") of August 1, 1969, the city's population roughly doubled, and the Sieg District was merged with the Bonn District to form the Rhein-Sieg District.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The formerly independent cities of Bad Godesberg and Beuel and the municipality of Duisdorf became independent boroughs of Bonn.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The borough of Beuel, on the right bank of the Rhine, was also assigned the villages of Holzlar, Hoholz, and the Oberkassel administrative area, which had previously belonged to the Sieg District.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Bonn itself was expanded with the villages of Ippendorf, Röttgen, Ückesdorf, Lessenich/Meßdorf, and Buschdorf from the former Bonn District, while Lengsdorf and Duisdorf, along with some new housing developments, formed the borough of Hardtberg.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The city of Bad Godesberg had already incorporated several villages earlier.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] As early as 1899, Plittersdorf and Rüngsdorf had joined Godesberg, and in 1904, Friesdorf was added, effectively merging Bad Godesberg with Bonn.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] In 1915, Bad Godesberg expanded southwest out of the valley, leading to the incorporation of Muffendorf.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] On July 1, 1935, Lannesdorf and Mehlem became districts of Bad Godesberg.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The current mayor of Bonn is Guido Déus of Christian Democratic Union of Germany since 2025.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] He defeated incumbent mayor Katja Dörner in the most recent mayoral election, which was held on 14 September 2025, with a runoff held on 28 September.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The Bonn city council governs the city alongside the mayor.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] It used to be based in the Rococo-style **Altes Rathaus** (old city hall), built in 1737, located adjacent to Bonn's central market square.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] However, due to the enlargement of Bonn in 1969 through the incorporation of Beuel and Bad Godesberg, it moved into the larger Stadthaus facilities further north.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] This was necessary for the city council to accommodate an increased number of representatives.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The mayor of Bonn still sits in the **Altes Rathaus**, which is also used for representative and official purposes.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Four delegates represent the Federal city of Bonn in the Landtag of North Rhine-Westphalia.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The last election took place in May 2022.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The current delegates are Guido Déus (CDU), Christos Katzidis (CDU), Joachim Stamp (FDP), Tim Achtermeyer (Greens) and Dr.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Bonn's constituency is called **Bundeswahlkreis Bonn** (096).
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] In the German federal election 2017, Ulrich Kelber (SPD) was elected a member of German Federal parliament, the Bundestag by direct mandate.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Katja Dörner representing Bündnis 90/Die Grünen and Alexander Graf Lambsdorff for FDP were elected as well.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Kelber resigned in 2019 because he was appointed Federal Commissioner for Data Protection and Freedom of Information.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] As Dörner was elected Lord Mayor of Bonn in September 2020, she resigned as a member of parliament after her entry into office.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Beethoven's birthplace is located in Bonngasse near the market place.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Next to the market place is the Old City Hall, built in 1737 in Rococo style, under the rule of Clemens August of Bavaria.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] It is used for receptions of guests of the city, and as an office for the mayor.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Nearby is the *Kurfürstliches Schloss*, built as a residence for the prince-elector and now the main building of the University of Bonn.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The *Poppelsdorfer Allee* is an avenue flanked by chestnut trees which had the first horsecar of the city.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] It connects the *Kurfürstliches Schloss* with the *Poppelsdorfer Schloss*, a palace that was built as a resort for the prince-electors in the first half of the 18th century, and whose grounds are now a botanical garden (the Botanischer Garten Bonn).
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] This axis is interrupted by a railway line and Bonn Hauptbahnhof, a building erected in 1883/84.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The Beethoven Monument stands on the Münsterplatz, which is flanked by the Bonn Minster, one of Germany's oldest churches.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] In its permanent exhibition, the Haus der Geschichte presents German history from 1945 until the present, also shedding light on Bonn's own role as former capital of West Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Numerous temporary exhibitions emphasize different features, such as Nazism or important personalities in German history.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The *Kunstmuseum Bonn* or Bonn Museum of Modern Art is an art museum founded in 1947.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The Kunstmuseum exhibits both temporary exhibitions and its permanent collection.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The latter is focused on Rhenish Expressionism and post-war German art.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] German artists on display include Georg Baselitz, Joseph Beuys, Hanne Darboven, Anselm Kiefer, Blinky Palermo and Wolf Vostell.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The museum owns one of the largest collections of artwork by Expressionist painter August Macke.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] His work is also on display in the August-Macke-Haus, located in Macke's former home where he lived from 1911 to 1914.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The *Bundeskunsthalle* (full name: Kunst- und Ausstellungshalle der Bundesrepublik Deutschland or Art and Exhibition Hall of the Federal Republic of Germany), focuses on the crossroads of culture, arts, and science.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] To date, it attracted more than 17 million visitors.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] One of its main objectives is to show the cultural heritage outside of Germany or Europe.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Next to its changing exhibitions, the Bundeskunsthalle regularly hosts concerts, discussion panels, congresses, and lectures.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The *Museum Koenig* is Bonn's natural history museum.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Affiliated with the University of Bonn, it is also a zoological research institution housing the *Leibniz-Institut für Biodiversität der Tiere*.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Politically interesting, it is on the premises of the Museum Koenig where the Parlamentarischer Rat first met.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The *Deutsches Museum Bonn*, affiliated with one of the world's foremost science museums, the Deutsches Museum in Munich, is an interactive science museum focusing on post-war German scientists, engineers, and inventions.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Other museums include the Beethoven House, birthplace of Ludwig van Beethoven, the Rheinisches Landesmuseum Bonn (Rhinish Regional Museum Bonn), the Bonn Women's Museum, the Rheinisches Malermuseum and the Arithmeum.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] There are several parks, leisure and protected areas in and around Bonn.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The *Rheinaue* is Bonn's most important leisure park, with its role being comparable to what Central Park is for New York City.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] It lies on the banks of the Rhine and is the city's biggest park intra muros.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The Rhine promenade and the *Alter Zoll* (Old Toll Station) are in direct neighbourhood of the city centre and are popular amongst both residents and visitors.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The *Arboretum Park Härle* is an arboretum with specimens dating to back to 1870.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The *Botanischer Garten* (Botanical Garden) is affiliated with the university.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The natural reserve of *Kottenforst* is a large area of protected woods on the hills west of the city centre.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] It is about 40 square kilometres (15 square miles) in area and part of the Rhineland Nature Park (1,045 km2 or 403 sq mi).
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] In the very south of the city, on the border with Wachtberg and Rhineland-Palatinate, there is an extinct volcano, the Rodderberg, featuring a popular area for hikes.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Also south of the city, there is the Siebengebirge which is part of the lower half of the Middle Rhine region.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The nearby upper half of the Middle Rhine from Bingen to Koblenz is a UNESCO World Heritage Site with more than 40 castles and fortresses from the Middle Ages and important German vineyards.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Named after Konrad Adenauer, the first post-war Chancellor of West Germany, Cologne Bonn Airport is situated 15 kilometres (9.3 miles) north-east from the city centre of Bonn.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] With around 10.3 million passengers passing through it in 2015, it is the seventh-largest passenger airport in Germany and the third-largest in terms of cargo operations.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] By traffic units, which combines cargo and passengers, the airport is in fifth position in Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] As of March 2015, Cologne Bonn Airport had services to 115 passenger destinations in 35 countries.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The airport is one of Germany's few 24-hour airports, and is a hub for Eurowings and cargo operators FedEx Express and UPS Airlines.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The federal motorway (*Autobahn*) A59 connects the airport with the city.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Long distance and regional trains to and from the airport stop at Cologne/Bonn Airport station.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Another major airport within a one-hour drive by car is Düsseldorf International Airport.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Bonn's central railway station, Bonn Hauptbahnhof is the city's main public transportation hub.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] It lies just outside the old town and near the central university buildings.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] It is served by regional (S-Bahn and Regionalbahn) and long-distance (IC and ICE) trains.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Daily, more than 67,000 people travel via Bonn Hauptbahnhof.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] In late 2016, around 80 long distance and more than 165 regional trains departed to or from Bonn every day.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Another long-distance station, (Siegburg/Bonn), is located in the nearby town of Siegburg and serves as Bonn's station on the high-speed rail line between Cologne and Frankfurt, offering faster connections to Southern Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] It can be reached by Stadtbahn line 66 (approx.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Bonn has a Stadtbahn light rail and a tram system.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The Bonn Stadtbahn has 4 regular lines that connect the main north–south axis (centre to Bad Godesberg) and quarters east of the Rhine (Beuel and Oberkassel), as well as many nearby towns like Brühl, Wesseling, Sankt Augustin, Siegburg, Königswinter, and Bad Honnef.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] All lines serve the Central Station and two lines continue to Cologne, where they connect to the Cologne Stadtbahn.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The Bonn tram system consists of two lines that connect closer quarters in the south, north and east of Bonn to the Central Station.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] While the Stadtbahn mostly has its own right-of-way, the tram often operates on general road lanes.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] A few sections of track are used by both systems.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] These urban rail lines are supplemented by a bus system of roughly 30 regular lines, especially since some parts of the city like Hardtberg and most of Bad Godesberg completely lack a Stadtbahn/Tram connection.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Several lines offer night services, especially during the weekends.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Bonn is part of the Verkehrsverbund Rhein-Sieg (*Rhine-Sieg Transport Association*) which is the public transport association covering the area of the Cologne/Bonn Region.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Three Bundesstraßen, which have a general 100 kilometres per hour (62 miles per hour) speed limit in contrast to the Autobahn, connect Bonn to its immediate surroundings (Bundesstraßen B9, B42 and B56).
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] With Bonn being divided into two parts by the Rhine, three bridges are crucial for inner-city road traffic: the Konrad-Adenauer-Brücke (A562) in the South, the Friedrich-Ebert-Brücke (A565) in the North, and the Kennedybrücke (B56) in the centre.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] In addition, regular ferries operate between Bonn-Mehlem and Königswinter, Bonn-Bad Godesberg and Königswinter-Niederdollendorf, and Bonn-Graurheindorf and Niederkassel-Mondorf.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Located in the northern sub-district of Graurheindorf, the inland harbour of Bonn is used for container traffic as well as oversea transport.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Regular passenger transport occurs to Cologne and Düsseldorf.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The head offices of Deutsche Telekom, its subsidiary Telekom Deutschland, Deutsche Post, German Academic Exchange Service, and SolarWorld are in Bonn.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The third largest employer in the city of Bonn is the University of Bonn (including the university clinics) and Stadtwerke Bonn also follows as a major employer.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] On the other hand, there are several traditional, nationally known private companies in Bonn such as luxury food producers Verpoorten and Kessko, the Klais organ manufacture and the Bonn flag factory.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The largest confectionery manufacturer in Europe, Haribo, has its founding headquarters (founded in 1920) and a production site in Bonn.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Since April 2018, the head office of the company is located in the Rhineland-Palatinate municipality of Grafschaft.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Other companies of supraregional importance are Weck Glaswerke (production site), Fairtrade, Eaton Industries (formerly Klöckner & Moeller), IVG Immobilien, Kautex Textron, SolarWorld, Vapiano and the Doxis.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The Rheinische Friedrich Wilhelms Universität Bonn (University of Bonn) is one of the largest universities in Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] It is also the location of the German research institute Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft (DFG) offices and of the German Academic Exchange Service (*Deutscher Akademischer Austauschdienst* – DAAD).
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] About 70% of the population was entirely of German origin, while about 100,000 people, equating to roughly 30%, were at least partly of non-German origin.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The city is one of the fastest-growing municipalities in Germany and the 18th most populous city in the country.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Bonn's population is predicted to surpass the populations of Wuppertal and Bochum before the year 2030.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The following list shows the largest groups of origin of minorities with "migration background" in Bonn as of 31 December 2021.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Bonn is home of the Telekom Baskets Bonn, the only basketball club in Germany that owns its arena, the Telekom Dome.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The city also has a semi-professional football team Bonner SC which was formed in 1965 through the merger of *Bonner FV* and *Tura Bonn*.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The Bonn Gamecocks American football team play at the 12,000-capacity Stadion Pennenfeld.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The successful German Baseball team Bonn Capitals are also found in the city of Bonn.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The headquarters of the International Paralympic Committee has been located in Bonn since 1999.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] Central Bonn is surrounded by a number of traditional towns and villages which were independent up to several decades ago.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] As many of those communities had already established their own contacts and partnerships before the regional and local reorganisation in 1969, the Federal City of Bonn now has a dense network of city district partnerships with European partner towns.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The city district of Bonn is a partner of the English university city of Oxford, England, UK (since 1947), of Budafok, District XXII of Budapest, Hungary (since 1991) and of Opole, Poland (officially since 1997; contacts were established 1954).
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The district of Bad Godesberg has established partnerships with Saint-Cloud in France, Frascati in Italy, Windsor and Maidenhead in England, UK and Kortrijk in Belgium; a friendship agreement has been signed with the town of Yalova, Turkey.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] The district of Beuel on the right bank of the Rhine and the city district of Hardtberg foster partnerships with towns in France: Mirecourt and Villemomble.
[src:alois-mertes/bonn] For twin towns of other city districts, see Bad Godesberg, Beuel and Hardtberg.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The **Breda Four** (**Breda Three** after 1966 and **Breda Two** after 1979), were the last four continuously imprisoned German war criminals in the Netherlands following the Second World War.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The group consisted of Willy Lages, Joseph Kotalla, Ferdinand aus der Fünten, and Franz Fischer.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] From 1952, they were incarcerated in the dome prison in Breda, which inspired their collective name.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Lages, Aus der Fünten and Fischer played a key role in the deportations of Jews, while Kotalla was deputy head of Kamp Amersfoort.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The Breda Four were initially sentenced to death, but in 1951–1952 were among those whose sentences were commuted to life imprisonment.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] However, they were the only German war criminals in the Netherlands not released before 1961.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In the following decades, pushes were made to release them.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The West German government and other organisations lobbied for them.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The clemency requests coincided with increasing awareness of World War II and the psychological impact on victims in the Netherlands.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Ministers of Justice decided against releasing them, after proposals for release were met with public protests and emotional debates in parliament.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Lages was released on sick leave in 1966 and died five years later in Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In 1987, Aus der Fünten and Fischer became the last German war criminals in Europe who had been continuously imprisoned since 1945.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] They were given clemency on 27 January 1989 and died the same year.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] As part of the Special Jurisdiction, the Breda Four were among the 240–242 Germans tried for war crimes and crimes against humanity in the Netherlands after the Second World War.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Eighteen Germans, including the Breda Four, were sentenced to the death penalty, which had been reintroduced for the Special Jurisdiction.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Franz Fischer (born 1901) was transferred to the *Referat IV-B4* in The Hague in November 1940.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Although Wilhelm Zoepf was the head, Fischer was in practice in daily charge of the deportation of 13,000 Jews and the tracking down of Jews in hiding.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] He was spared the death penalty and instead received a life sentence on 17 March 1949, after the judge ruled that his personality disorder diminished his responsibility and that his antisemitic beliefs stemmed from prolonged exposure to propaganda.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] This was overturned in cassation on 12 July 1950, when he was sentenced to death.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Willy Lages (born 1901) became head of the Amsterdam office of the *Sicherheitspolizei* and the *Sicherheitsdienst* in Amsterdam after the February strike in 1941, as well as head of the Central Agency for Jewish Emigration in Amsterdam.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] He was responsible for anti-Jewish measures, including roundups and deportations of 70,000 Jews.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] He was involved in executions, including of Hannie Schaft and within *Operation Silbertanne*.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] He was sentenced to death on 20 September 1949, which was upheld in cassation on 12 July 1950.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Ferdinand aus der Fünten (born 1909) joined the Central Agency for Jewish Emigration in Amsterdam in September 1941.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] He eventually became deputy chief under Lages, through which he took daily charge of the deportations in Amsterdam.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] He was also involved in the clearance of various institutions, including Het Apeldoornsche Bosch.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The court initially sentenced him to life in prison in December 1949, but this was overturned in cassation and he was sentenced to death on 12 July 1950.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Joseph Kotalla (born 1908) was appointed as a guard in the Police Prison in Scheveningen in February 1941, where he was considered to be one of the worst.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In September 1941, he was moved to Kamp Amersfoort as punishment for mishandling a prisoner in a cell.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Nevertheless, Kotalla became head of administration and de facto deputy commander in early 1943.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] His harsh and violent treatment of prisoners earned him the nickname "Executioner of Amersfoort".
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] He was sentenced to death both at the initial trial and in cassation.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Despite public support for the death penalty, the Schermerhorn–Drees cabinet feared that too many executions would negatively impact society.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In February 1946, the cabinet adopted secret guidelines for clemency.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In January 1947, Minister of Justice Johannes Henricus van Maarseveen (KVP) included the most serious German war criminals as a category eligible for execution.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The clemency policy faced criticism from the judicial branch, Queen Wilhelmina – who temporarily refused to approve clemencies in 1947 – and various parties in parliament.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Meanwhile in West Germany, a lobby started for war criminals, which were euphemistically called 'prisoners of war'.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] This aid was started by the churches, in the case of the Breda Four primarily the Protestant church.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Organisations linked to the churches provided legal aid, supported by government subsidies since 1948.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In particular, president of the Evangelical Church of the Palatinate Hans Stempel was active, visiting the prisoners at Christmas 1951 and representing their interest ever since.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In 1952, he became a board member of the *Stille Hilfe*.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In March 1952, chair of the Evangelical Church in Germany, Otto Dibelius, protested in a letter to prime minister Willem Drees against the death sentences and asked for commutation to life in prison.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In 1949, the West German government formed the Central Legal Protection Office to coordinate the legal aid to German prisoners abroad.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The West German government tried to prevent the execution of the death penalty.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] On 25 March 1950, German Chancellor Konrad Adenauer (CDU) asked the chairman of the Allied High Commission, André François-Poncet, to request that the Dutch government refrain from carrying out the death sentences.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Through diplomatic channels, the West German government would continue in the next decades to bring up the release of the German war criminals.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In 1948, Juliana ascended to the throne as the new queen.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] She held conscientious objections to the death penalty and refused to deny some clemency requests.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Minister of Justice Teun Struycken (KVP) reached a compromise with Juliana.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The death penalty would be carried out only if both the initial trial and the cassation resulted in a death sentence.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Consequently, the sentences of Aus der Fünten and Fischer were commuted to life imprisonment in January 1951, while Julius Herdtmann was executed in exchange.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The commutation sparked indignation, particularly among the former Dutch resistance and Jewish organisations.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] On 22 May 1951, communist parliamentarian Benno Stokvis interpellated Struycken's successor, Hendrik Mulderije (CHU), regarding the clemency policy.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Stokvis, along with the Anti-Revolutionary Party (ARP) and the CHU, criticised the policy.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] A significant majority, led by KVP and Labour Party (PvdA), opposed a motion tabled by Stokvis to publish the clemency guidelines.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] However, a majority supported a motion tabled by Leen Donker (PvdA), expressing concern about the potential conversion of life sentences into temporary ones.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] During Kotalla's trial, the question arose whether he had diminished responsibility .
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] After his trials, he was diagnosed with obsessive-compulsive disorder as a result of brain damage suffered at the age of nine.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] As a result, Mulderije reduced Kotalla's sentence to life imprisonment in December 1951 due to diminished responsibility.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Lages had been sentenced in cassation in July 1950, after which he directly requested clemency.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Both courts opposed clemency, but it took the Special Court of Cassation until September 1951 to reach this conclusion.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The delay was attributed to the head prosecutor delaying the processing of the request and using Lages for his investigation into abuses in camps for political detainees.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Juliana also opposed his execution, while Mulderije refused to approve the clemency, both threatening to resign.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Because neither gave in, a decision was postponed until after the 25 June 1952 election.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In the new second Drees cabinet, Donker became minister of Justice.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The long time between his sentence and the execution became the main reason for Donker to commute Lages' sentence to life imprisonment on 29 September 1952.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The decision to commute Lages' sentence sparked social unrest, with a protest on 12 October 1952 in Amsterdam involving 15,000 to 20,000 demonstrators opposing the commutation.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Donker made the reservation in parliament that, as far as he was concerned, there would be no question of a second commutation in this exceptional category.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] He also said that in his opinion ministerial accountability applied to clemency decisions.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] This meant that such a decision would be influenced by parliament and thus society.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Since the introduction of the Criminal Code in 1886, a life sentence in the Netherlands had never not been commuted (generally after 15–17 years).
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Former Minister Struycken later stated that he expected the commuted death sentence to mean a maximum of 20 years in prison.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In addition, the Dutch government wanted to leave the war behind through clemency, amongst others to avoid controversial debates about Dutch collaboration.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] This led to the release of the last German war criminals except for the Breda Four in 1961.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] This included the five other German prisoners initially sentenced to death, who were released between December 1958 and May 1960 in relative silence.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] There were a few reasons why the Breda Four were not released.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Their cases had stirred the public opinion since directly after the war, and their first commutation had already led to public outcry and a parliamentary resolution against a further commutation.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The public interest in the Second World War increased in the early 1960s, with the Eichmann trial (1961), the release of Jacques Pressers book *Ashes in the Wind: The Destruction of Dutch Jewry* (1965) and the broadcasting of Loe de Jongs television series *De bezetting* (The occupation, 1960–1965).
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] During a debate in 1959, Minister of Justice Albert Beerman (CHU) said the Four would qualify for clemency and emphasised that clemency was a prerogative of the Crown.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Encouraged by Beerman, progressive criminal law experts Jacob Maarten van Bemmelen and Willem Pompe pleaded in *Nederlands Juristenblad* in 1963 for the release of the four prisoners.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The publicity backfired and led to public outrage, which made Beerman refrain from clemency.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Former chairs of the Foundation Supervision of the Political Offenders (Dutch: *Stichting Toezicht Politieke Delinquenten*, STPD) Frans Duynstee and Jaap le Poole wrote a reaction in support of Pompe's and Van Bemmelen's article a month after its publication.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Le Poole, who had been active in the resistance and was a former PvdA MP, continued behind the scenes to convince influential individuals of clemency.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] He introduced Stempel to various Dutch journalists and politicians.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] A month after Van Bemmelen and Pompe, the bishop of the Diocese of 's-Hertogenbosch, Wilhelmus Marinus Bekkers, also publicly argued for a pardon.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In September 1964, the auxilary bishop of Cologne Wilhelm Cleven met with Beerman's successor Ynso Scholten (CHU) to ask for the release of the Breda Four at some point on behalf of the German Episcopate.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Although Scholten believed they could not remain in Dutch prison for the rest of their lives, he saw insufficient parliamentary support and rejected their clemency requests on 24 October 1964.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Le Poole had some success with Ivo Samkalden (PvdA), who had started as Minister of Justice on 14 April 1965.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] He rejected collective clemency, but was open to individual clemency, in particular for Kotalla given his psychiatric evaluations.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Meanwhile, the Supreme Court also changed its advice on clemency for Kotalla, from negative in 1960 to positive in 1962 and 1963.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Public opinion and the view from National Institute for War Documentation historian Ben Sijes that release might hinder the prosecution of war criminals in Germany and Austria, prevented Samkalden from giving clemency.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Samkalden also wanted to wait until after the controversial wedding between the Dutch crown princess Beatrix and the German Claus von Amsberg in March 1966.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In May 1966, Lages was hospitalised with colorectal cancer and doctors did not expect him to survive surgery.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] After Le Poole brought this to the attention of Samkalden, Samkalden granted a three-month suspension of his sentence to receive treatment in Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] He was transferred to a hospital in Braunlage on 9 June 1966.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] When German ambassador Karl Hermann Knoke was informed the day before, he also asked for the release of Kotalla who had a heart condition, which Samkalden refused.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] There was a disgruntled reaction to Lages' release from the former resistance and war victims.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] A demonstration of 150 people took place in Amsterdam.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] There was also commotion within Samkaldens own party, with some Jewish members expressing disbelief that the Jewish Samkalden had made this decision.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Despite the unrest, the decision was accepted by the coalition parties.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Less than a month later, Samkalden was informed that Lages did not have cancer, but severe bowel obstruction as a result of polyarteritis nodosa.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] This was life threatening, but not acutely fatal.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] He was unable to imprison Lages again, because of Lages' medical condition and the fact that the West German constitution did not allow extradition.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] 2,000 protesters showed up for another protest in Amsterdam.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] During a debate in the House on 4 October 1966, Samkalen kept the support of the coalition parties and the CHU.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Lages was released from the hospital in November 1966, but stayed in Braunlage, where he died in 1971.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Lages' controversial release complicated in the subsequent years the pardoning of the other three, particularly Kotalla, who was suffering from heart disease.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The West German government paused their interventions for a while.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In June 1967, their lawyer filed new clemency requests.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] At the request of German Foreign Minister Willy Brandt (SPD), North Rhine-Westphalian Minister of Justice, Josef Neuberger (SPD) brought up the release in a meeting with the new Duch Minister of Justice Carel Polak (VVD).
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Polak preferred amending the Criminal Code to allow for the conditional release of those sentenced to life imprisonment after twenty years over clemency.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] This way, the process would be transparent and with the involvement of parliament.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In consultation with the Council of Ministers, he confidentially gauged the opinions of the parliamentary leaders in August 1969.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] There was significant division within the parliamentary groups, but a majority of 85 members supported the proposal.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The confidential consultation leaked, leading to societal unrest, particularly among former resistance groups and Jewish communities.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] On the other hand there were supports; Churches and rehabilitation associations advocated for release, and the four Bureaus for Mental Public Health argued that detaining the Three would relieve no sorrow for victims.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Despite parliamentary support, Polak sent a letter to parliament on 29 September 1969 withdrawing his proposal.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] On 21 October 1969, the issue came up in the House during a debate about the Justice budget.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Parliamentarian Theo van Schaik (KVP), a former student of Pompe, had announced his intention to submit a motion urging the cabinet to introduce the bill, despite Polak's attempts to dissuade him.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] During the debate, Van Schaik argued that the bill would provide legal equality.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] He also contended that the Dutch population suffered from the presence of the Three and that life imprisonment obscured the sense of justice within the legal system.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] As a final argument, he stated that it was intolerable for the Three to repeatedly be filled with hope only to be rejected without prospect.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] After this final argument, loud outbursts erupted from the gallery, and the debate was interrupted.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In the debate, the motion faced criticism from parliamentarians.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] A point of criticism was that the motion used the commotion, which it itself fueled, as an argument.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Another point was that a general legislative amendment was being used when the issue was specifically about the Three.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] During the second round of the debate, Polak managed to persuade Van Schaik to withdraw the motion.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] According to Van Schaik, the resistance was too great.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Polak subsequently denied the clemency requests.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In 1971, Dries van Agt (KVP) took office as Minister of Justice.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Within the field of criminal law, he was considered progressive.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] During his first meeting with journalists, he indicated that he planned to release the Breda Three.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In what he later referred to as self-deprecating humor, Van Agt remarked that it would probably be more difficult for him as an "Aryan" than it had been for his predecessor.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] This comment immediately sparked outrage.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] During a debate in October 1971, Van Agt promised that he would consult the House before releasing the Three.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] After receiving positive and unanimous advice from the judiciary, the cabinet wanted to proceed with clemency.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] They consulted the parliamentary leaders, which revealed that a majority would agree.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] On 16 February 1972, the cabinet sent a letter about the intention to the House.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The proposal for release was made during a period of increased focus on the suffering of war victims.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] This attention was partly due to the research conducted by psychiatrist Jan Bastiaans and his documentary *Now Do You Get It Why I'm Crying?* (1969).
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The plan to release them received extensive media attention and stirred strong emotions.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] War victims and former resistance fighters established an umbrella organisation, the Central Organisation of Former Resistance and Victims 1940–1945 (COVVS), with the primary aim of preventing the release of the Breda Three.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In this effort, both communist and non-communist resistance organisations collaborated after decades of rivalry.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] There was also pressure from abroad, with the Israeli cabinet objecting to their release.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Many parliamentarians received phone calls at home, including threats, and Van Agt had to go into hiding with his family.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Although the cabinet had hoped that the House would refrain from a painful discussion, a hearing was initiated by Anneke Goudsmit (D'66).
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The decisive factor was Goudsmit's remark that victims never had the opportunity to bring up the suffering they had endured in parliament.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] A day before the hearing, the documentary "Now Do You Get It Why I'm Crying?" was shown to members of parliament, which made many of them doubtful already, and three days later on national television.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] During the hearing on 24 February 1972, 50 speakers representing 43 organisations spoke, the majority of whom were against release.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The hearing was emotional, as became evident from the commotion surrounding a speech by criminal law scholar Louk Hulsman on behalf of the association for criminal law reform, Coornhert-Liga.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] After three psychiatrists, including Bastiaans, argued that releasing the Breda Three would have negative consequences for the victims, Hulsman advocated for release.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] When he argued that keeping the Breda Three in prison did not help the victims, shouts of "Yes, it does" came from the spectators.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The hearing had to be temporarily halted because there was a threat of physical altercation among spectators.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The hearings and public discussion had persuaded a significant number of members of parliament to vote against the release.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Despite the opposition to the release, Van Agt wanted to proceed.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] According to him, the expulsion of the Three was preferable to repeatedly reopening wounds that had only partially healed.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] On 29 February 1972, the debate on the release lasted thirteen hours.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] As the debate progressed, there was increasing applause and shouting from the public gallery.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] A motion tabled by Joop Voogd (PvdA) calling for the Three not to be released was adopted with 85 votes in favor and 61 against.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] A large number of parties were divided in their voting.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] On 3 and 4 March, the cabinet discussed the outcome of the debate.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Amongst others, ministers Kees Boertien (ARP), Van Agt, Piet Engels, and Pierre Lardinois (both KVP) wanted the cabinet to proceed with granting clemency.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Others, including Norbert Schmelzer (KVP) and Hans de Koster (VVD), were opposed.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Molly Geertsema (VVD), who had always been against the release, even threatened to resign if they were released, according to *De Tijd*.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The initial draft proposal was to release Fischer, keep the clemency request of Kotalla, and to reject that of Aus der Fünten.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] However, due to objections, this plan was reconsidered.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Ultimately, on 4 March, the cabinet presented a statement in which they abandoned the collective release.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The cabinet emphasised that it retained the right to grant clemency on an individual basis.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] They announced additional examinations into the physical and mental condition of the detainees.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In the event of any clemency, the cabinet stated that they would seek advice from experts, including individuals who are trusted in circles of resistance members and victims.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The debate on the release also contributed to provisions for victims of World War II.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] To get advice from resistance members and the persecuted, a "trust committee" was established with a delegation of seven members from COVVS.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] This committee, whose composition changed over time, consisted at the start solely of opponents of the release, including Hans Teengs Gerritsen (chairman) and Herman Milikowski.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In addition to the government examination, they appointed their own medical expert, Hans Hers, to determine the health condition of the detainees.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] On 30 October 1973, Kotalla suffered a hemorrhagic stroke, resulting in partial paralysis.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] His health deteriorated further due to a pulmonary embolism he contracted in the hospital, leading officials and the minister to believe that he would not survive.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Hers visited Kotalla in the hospital and concluded that although Kotalla was in poor condition, he was not yet in the dying phase.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The trust committee remained opposed to release, although they understood if the minister decided to proceed with it.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Due to a lack of support, Van Agt refrained from granting clemency.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] From the German side, the stroke was a reason for renewed pressure.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Priest Ernst Wilms, who advocated for the last imprisoned German war criminals in Europe, sent a telegram to the ministry urging the release of the Three.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The German ambassador to the Netherlands, Adolf Max Obermayer, also insisted on it, but without success.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] It was not until December 1974 that Kotalla was transferred from the hospital back to Breda, a move he had pushed for, in part, through a hunger strike.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] His lawyer Nouwen filed for a preliminary injunction, arguing amongst other that prolonged detention of Kotalla was inhumane.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] When this failed, he appealed all the way up to the European Court of Human Rights, where it was also rejected.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In subsequent years, Kotalla's physical and mental health continued to decline.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] A prison doctor concluded around June 1979 that Kotalla's death was near.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The new minister of Justice, Job de Ruiter (CDA), made preparations for release and sent Hers to visit Kotalla on 6 July 1979.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Hers told the trust committee he was not able to say how long Kotalla was going to live, but that he was not in immediate life-threatening danger.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Based on this, the trust committee opposed release as he was not "in the eye of death".
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Without their support, De Ruiter considers releasing Kotalla political suicide, so he decided not to proceed.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In the next weeks, Kotalla's health detoriated further.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Despite the pleas from his caregivers, Kotalla was neither re-examined nor released.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] On 31 July 1979, Kotalla died in prison.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] He was the only convicted German war criminal who died in the Dutch prison.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In 1982, Frits Korthals Altes (VVD) became Minister of Justice.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] His strategy was to address the topic of the Breda Two as little as possible in order to prevent unrest among victims.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Nevertheless, there was publicity, especially when the Bundestag unanimously adopted a motion tabled by Alois Mertes (CDU) in 1982, which urged the release of amongst others Fischer and Aus der Fünten.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] On the advice of the German ambassador to the Netherlands, Otto von der Gablentz, this motion was not carried out, and Germany largely refrained from raising the issue.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] This approach was intended to convince the former resistance that there was no German pressure.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In the background, Bib van Lanschot particularly advocated for release.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In 1987, he had Fischer and Aus der Fünten send a letter to parliamentary leaders, several ministers, and resistance organisations.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The negative or dismissive reactions led to the conclusion that this was not the right approach.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Van Lanschot was involved in the Resistance Memorial Cross, which had to promote unity within the former resistance outside of the opposition to the release of the Breda Two.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Around the committee, a group of prominent figures, including resistance fighters and politicians, emerged who wanted to work towards their release.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Some of them, such as Teengs Gerritsen and Hers, had altered their views on the release as time progressed.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] To this end, they drew up a letter, which they presented to Korthals Altes and Prime Minister Ruud Lubbers on 5 July 1988.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] They pointed out, among other things, that the Netherlands was the last country where German war criminals had been continuously imprisoned since 1945.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Just before the visit of the group of nineteen, Korthals Altes had ordered an investigation into the medical condition of the prisoners due to concerning signals.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] However, the medical specialists concluded that their condition was not such that release for medical reasons was necessary.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] After the examination, Korthals Altes informed the group of nineteen on 5 January 1989 that the release would not be easily achieved.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Nevertheless, Korthals Altes decided to consult the parliamentary leaders about clemency with the help of a delegation of the group of nineteen.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Korthals Altes also met with the remaining members of the trust committee as well as Bastiaans, all of whom support the release.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] On 24 January 1989, he sent a letter to the House expressing his intention to release the Two.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In addition to the letter from the group of nineteen, he cited the expectation that the discussion would not subside, meaning the goal of sparing the victims would not be achieved.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] In his memoirs, Korthals Altes also says that the individual care they receive in detention might be life-prolonging, which would prolong the suffering of victims as well.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] He wanted to revisit, with the approval of the House, the commitment made in 1972 that simultaneous release would be refrained from.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The House acted quickly, without too much publicity.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] A hearing with representatives of victims and the resistance was held in private on Thursday 26 January.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] That same day, a two-day debate on the matter began, even though the House normally doesn't debate on Fridays.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The arguments exchanged during this debate were not substantially different from those in 1972, although far less emotional.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] A motion tabled by Ineke Haas-Berger (PvdA) to refrain from granting clemency except on an individual basis was rejected with 55 votes in favor and 85 votes against.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] A few hours after the debate, Fischer and Aus der Fünten were expelled across the border as undesirable foreigners.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] On the day of the release, German President Richard von Weizsäcker thanked the Dutch parliament for this decision.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] The German Foreign Office praised the Dutch government for using humanitarian reasons in its decisions and added that Fischer and Aus der Fünten would not receive a formal welcome.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Fischer and Aus der Fünten received a federal pension, after Fischer's North Rhine-Westphalian pension was revoked.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Their pension was supplemented by donations, including from *Stille Hilfe*.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Aus der Fünten died in April 1989, and Fischer died in September 1989.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Although the political debate ended with the release, public outrage continued for some time.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Three days after the release, the Auschwitz commemoration was attended by more people than usual in protest.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] There was a lot of discussion, especially within the former resistance, which focused on the members of the group of nineteen.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] Immediately following the debate, Teengs Gerritsen distanced himself from the group of nineteen.
[src:alois-mertes/breda-two] He said that he did not agree with everything in the letter and that his intention was solely to prevent further harm to the victims.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The **Bundestag** (German: [ˈbʊndəstaːk] ⓘ, 'Federal Diet') is the federal parliament of Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] It is the only constitutional body in the country directly elected by the German people.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The Bundestag was established by Title III of the Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany (*Grundgesetz*) in 1949 as one of the legislative bodies of Germany, the other being the Bundesrat.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The members of the Bundestag are representatives of the German people as a whole, are not bound by any orders or instructions and are only accountable to their conscience.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Since the current 21st legislative period, the Bundestag has a fixed number of 630 members.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The Bundestag is elected every four years by German citizens aged 18 and older.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Elections use a mixed-member proportional representation system which combines first-past-the-post voting for constituency-seats with proportional representation to ensure its composition mirrors the national popular vote.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The German Bundestag cannot dissolve itself; only the president of Germany can do so under certain conditions.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Together with the Bundesrat, the Bundestag forms the legislative branch of government at the federal level.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The Bundestag is considerably more powerful than the Bundesrat, which represents the state governments.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] All bills must first be passed in the Bundestag before they are discussed in the Bundesrat.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The Bundesrat can only accept laws passed by the Bundestag without amendment.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Only in some areas, where laws directly affect the states, can the Bundesrat reject laws; otherwise, it can only lodge an objection to them, which the Bundestag can overrule.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Above all, however, the chancellor and the federal government are solely responsible to the Bundestag.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The Bundestag also has sole budgetary authority.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Since 1999, the Bundestag has met in the Reichstag building in Berlin.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The Bundestag also operates in multiple new government buildings in Berlin around the neo-renaissance house and has its own police force (the *Bundestagspolizei*), directly subordinated to the Bundestag Presidency.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The Bundestag's presiding officer is the president of the Bundestag; they are deputized by the Vice Presidents of the Bundestag.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Since 2025, Julia Klöckner of the CDU/CSU is the president of the Bundestag.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] In the protocol order of the federation, the President of the Bundestag ranks second after the President and before the Chancellor.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The first body to be called Bundestag was the legislative body of the German Confederation, which convened in Frankfurt am Main from 1816 to 1866.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] This Bundestag was a convention of state envoys.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] During the revolution of 1848/49, the National Assembly, which met in Frankfurt am Main, was the first elected German parliament and served as a constituent assembly for a German state, which ultimately did not come to pass.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The North German Confederation, founded in 1866/67, was the first German nation state with an established elected parliament, however this ended up being called the Reichstag.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] In 1870/71, the federation was expanded to include the southern German territories and was henceforth called the German Empire.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The Reichstag building, where the current Bundestag meets since 1999 (see below), was built in 1888.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The German Empire was not yet a parliamentary democracy in the modern sense, but a constitutional monarchy with democratic elements.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The Reichstag had to approve all bills, had the right to initiate legislation and, in particular, had budgetary sovereignty.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] However, the Chancellor and the imperial government were not responsible to parliament, but to the emperor alone.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] It was not until 1918, a few weeks before the end of the First World War, that the Reichstag was given the right, as part of a constitutional reform, to withdraw its confidence in the Chancellor and thus force him to resign.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] There was also no universal suffrage for the Reichstag; only men over the age of 25 were entitled to vote in Reichstag elections.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] After its defeat in the First World War, Germany became a republic and a parliamentary democracy with the Weimar Constitution of 1919.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The voting age was lowered to 21 years and women were given the right to vote for (and serve in) the Reichstag.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] However, the first German democracy failed for various reasons, some of which were directly related to the Reichstag.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The pure proportional representation system in elections did not produce clear majorities and the various parties were not sufficiently willing to compromise to form stable governments.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] This led to numerous changes of government and snap elections.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] In the last years of the Weimar Republic, opposition parties on the far-right and the far-left held the majority of seats in the Reichstag, which led the governments to rule largely by emergency decrees and bypass parliament.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] In 1933, Adolf Hitler was appointed chancellor and through the Reichstag Fire Decree, the Enabling Act of 1933 and the death of President Paul von Hindenburg in 1934, gained unlimited power.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] After this, the Reichstag, in which only the Nazi Party was represented from November 1933 on, met only rarely, above all to extend the emergency laws on which the Nazi dictatorship was formally based.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] With the Basic Law of 1949, Germany's second democratic constitution, the Bundestag was established as the new parliament.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Due to the division of Germany, the Bundestag was de facto a West German parliament until 1990.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The socialist GDR in East Germany had its own parliament, the Volkskammer, which, however, did not emerge from democratic elections except for its last electoral term in 1990.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Because West Berlin was not officially under the jurisdiction of the Basic Law during the division, the Bundestag met in Bonn in several different buildings, including (provisionally) a former waterworks facility and finally in the Bundeshaus.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] In addition, owing to the city's legal status, citizens of West Berlin were unable to vote in elections to the Bundestag, and were instead represented by 22 non-voting delegates chosen by the House of Representatives, the city's legislature.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Since German reunification in 1990, the Bundestag has once again been an all-German parliament.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] In 1999, the German parliament moved from Bonn to Berlin and sits once again in the Reichstag building.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Together with the Bundesrat, the Bundestag forms the legislative branch of the German political system.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The Bundestag is one of three constitutional bodies (along with the Bundesrat and the federal government) that have the right of initiative for the legislative process.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] In order to introduce a bill in the Bundestag, the support of a faction or of a number of MPs corresponding to at least 5% of all MPs is required.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] All bills (including those introduced by the Bundesrat and the government) are first voted on in the Bundestag (for bills from the Bundesrat and the government, however, an opinion must first be obtained from the other body).
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] A bill is first discussed at first reading, then referred to one or more committees, where it can be amended; the resulting committee version then goes back to the plenary, where it is passed at second and third reading.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Amendments can also be tabled at this stage.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] A simple majority (more yes votes than no votes with no regard to abstentions) is required for normal legislative proposals.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] In some very rare cases, the Basic Law requires the so-called chancellor majority (majority of all members of parliament) for simple laws, for example to establish new intermediate and subordinate federal authorities.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Laws amending the Basic Law require a two-thirds majority of all members of the Bundestag.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] A law passed by the Bundestag is passed on to the Bundesrat.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Amendments to the Basic Law and laws that directly affect the states must be passed by the Bundesrat by majority vote (amendments to the Basic Law, again, by a two-thirds majority); all other laws are considered passed if the Bundesrat does not object to them within 14 days.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] In no case can the Bundesrat make amendments to a bill.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] If the Bundesrat rejects a bill, the matter is often referred to the so-called mediation committee, a body made up of an equal number of members of the Bundestag and Bundesrat, which attempts to negotiate whether the bill can find the approval of both chambers with certain amendments.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] A version amended in this way must then be passed again by a majority in both chambers in order to become law (in this case the rules of procedure of both chambers provide for an abbreviated legislative procedure).
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] In the final step, a law must be signed by the President of Germany (they have a right of veto in theory, but this has been used very rarely in the history of the Federal Republic).
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The Bundestag has an elective function for a number of offices.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The chancellor is elected by the Bundestag and formally appointed by the president of Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] A chancellor's election is necessary whenever the office of chancellor has fallen vacant.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] This is the case if a newly elected Bundestag meets for the first time, or during legislative periods, if the former chancellor died or resigned.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The chancellor's election is one of the few cases in which a vote in the Bundestag requires a majority of all elected members, not just a majority of those assembled at the time, the so-called *Kanzlermehrheit* ("chancellor majority").
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] As with other elections performed by the Bundestag, the chancellor is elected via secret ballot.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] If the nominee reaches the necessary "chancellor majority", the president appoints him or her and, after that, the president of the Bundestag will administer the oath of office before the assembled house.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] If this nominee is not elected, the right of nomination is transferred onto the Bundestag: Candidates can now be nominated for election, whereby a nomination must be supported by at least a quarter of all MPs.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The Bundestag can hold any number of ballots in this manner for two weeks.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] To be elected, a candidate still needs a "chancellor majority" of yes-votes ("Second voting phase").
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] If the Bundestag is unable to elect a chancellor in these fourteen days, a final ballot is held on the very next day.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Once again, candidates can be nominated by at least a quarter of all MPs.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Candidates receiving a "chancellor majority" in this ballot are elected.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Otherwise, it is up to the President of Germany either to appoint the candidate with the plurality of votes as Chancellor or to dissolve the Bundestag and call new elections ("Third voting phase").
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Another possibility to vote a new chancellor into office is the constructive vote of no confidence, which allows the Bundestag to replace a sitting chancellor, if it elects a new chancellor with the "chancellor-majority".
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The Bundestag shares responsibility with the Bundesrat for electing the judges of the Federal Constitutional Court.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Both chambers elect four judges to each of the court's two senates.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] They also elect the president and vice-president of the Federal Constitutional Court in alternating order.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] In the Bundestag, this requires a two-thirds majority of members present, which has equal at least a majority of all members.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The majority ratios in the Bundestag therefore do not necessarily have to correspond to those in the Federal Assembly.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The Bundestag is elected for four years, and new elections must be held no earlier than 46 and no later than 48 months after the beginning of a given legislative term.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] By way of exception, there may be an early election if the President of Germany dissolves the Bundestag.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] However, the President only has the right to do so in the event of a failed chancellor election or if an incumbent chancellor requests dissolution after losing a vote of confidence.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The possibility of an early election is therefore in theory much more limited than is the case in some other parliamentary democracies.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] This restriction is intended to encourage the parliamentary groups to cooperate in difficult situations, and is a lesson learned from the experience of the Weimar Republic, in which snap elections were very frequent because the parties were unable to compromise and form stable governments.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] A legislative term ends at the moment when a newly-elected Bundestag convenes for the first time, which must occur within 30 days after an election.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The principle applies that there can be no "period without parliament".
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] An elected Bundestag is fully competent to act until a newly-elected Bundestag convenes for its first session.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Prorogations and dissolutions (in the strict sense), as known in the Westminster system, do not exist in Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Even an early dissolution of the Bundestag, as described above, in practice only leads to an early election, but does not end the legislative period itself.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Following the tradition of German parliamentarism, the Bundestag is subject to the *principle of discontinuation*, meaning that a newly-elected Bundestag is legally regarded as a body and entity completely different from the previous Bundestag.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] This leads to the result that any motion, application or action submitted to the previous Bundestag, e.g. a bill referred to the Bundestag by the Federal Government, is regarded as void by non-decision (German terminology: "*Die Sache fällt der Diskontinuität anheim*").
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Thus any bill that has not been decided upon by the beginning of the new electoral period must be brought up by the government again if it aims to uphold the motion, this procedure in effect delaying the passage of the bill.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Furthermore, any newly-elected Bundestag will have to freshly decide on the rules of procedure (*Geschäftsordnung*), which is done by a formal decision of taking over such rules from the preceding Bundestag by reference.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] If the succeeding Bundestag convenes with same or similar majorities like its predecessor, the parliament can decide to take over earlier initiatives of legislation in the same fashion to abbreviate the process, thus effectively breaking the principle of discontinuation by a pull.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Before an electoral reform in 2023, the Bundestag nominally had 598 members, with the mixture of majority and proportional representation regularly leading to a large number of additional overhang and compensation mandates.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Every elector has two votes: a constituency vote (first vote) and a party list vote (second vote).
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Based solely on the first votes, 299 members are elected in single-member constituencies by first-past-the-post voting.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The second votes are used to produce proportionality with respect to the total number of 630 seats; first at the federal level and then at state level (using the Sainte-Laguë method).
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] In most cases, the number of constituencies won by a party in a given state does not exactly correspond to the number of seats to which the party is entitled in that state via second votes.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] To qualify for any seats, however, a party must either win three single-member constituencies via first votes (basic mandate clause) or exceed a threshold of 5% of the second votes nationwide.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] This does not apply to independent constituency candidates: these always enter the Bundestag if they win their constituency.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] (However, no independent constituency candidate has won a constituency since 1949).
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Seats allocated in this way are subtracted from the base number of 630 when the mandates are distributed among the parties.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] In addition, the second votes of voters who have elected a successful independent candidate in a constituency are not taken into account when calculating the number of mandates (although they are for the 5% threshold).
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Parties representing recognized national minorities (currently Danes, Frisians, Sorbs, and Romani people) are exempt from both the 5% national threshold and the basic mandate clause.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The only party that has been able to benefit from this provision so far at the federal level is the South Schleswig Voters' Association, which represents the minorities of Danes and Frisians in Schleswig-Holstein, and succeeded in winning a seat in 1949, 2021, and 2025.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] If a member of parliament leaves the Bundestag during the current legislative term, either through resignation or death, another candidate from that party from the corresponding state takes their place.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Successful constituency candidates who did not receive a seat in the previous election due to the principle of second vote coverage are considered first, followed by the candidates on the respective state list.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] However, if the list is exhausted, the seat in question remains vacant for the remainder of the term.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] If the departing member was an independent constituency candidate, the seat also remains empty.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The latest federal election was held on Sunday, 23 February 2025, to elect the members of the 21st Bundestag.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The executive bodies of the Bundestag are the Presidium and the Council of Elders.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The Presidium consists of the President, the presiding officer, and several Vice Presidents.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The President and Vice Presidents are elected by the plenary of the Bundestag, whereby traditionally the largest fraction nominates the President and each fraction may nominate a vice president.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] In addition to the members of the Presidium, the Council of Elders includes 23 other deputies who are delegated proportionally by the factions.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The council is the coordination hub, determining the daily legislative agenda and assigning committee chairpersons based on Parliamentary group representation.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The council also serves as an important forum for interparty negotiations on specific legislation and procedural issues.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The Presidium is responsible for the routine administration of the Bundestag, including its clerical and research activities.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The Bundestag cannot be adjourned or prorogued during the current legislative term, but is always fully capable of acting and sets its own legislative calendar.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Normally, the Bundestag sits for at least twenty weeks per year, interrupted by non-sessional weeks, especially a long parliamentary summer recess, during which the MPs are present in their constituencies.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The course of a session week is traditionally always the same: meetings of the parliamentary faction's internal committees take place on Monday and Tuesday mornings, and meetings in the faction-plenary on Tuesday afternoon.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] From Wednesday to Friday, plenary sessions and committee meetings take place in parallel (this is the reason why often very few members are present at plenary debates).
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Committee meetings are interrupted on very important items on the agenda so that all MPs have the opportunity to be present in the plenary hall.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The highlights of the procedures include government statements by the Chancellor and the general debate at the beginning of the annual budget deliberations, during which there is a direct clash between the Chancellor and the opposition leader.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Independently of the usual procedure, the Bundestag can also convene for extraordinary sessions at any time.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] This must happen if one third of the MPs, the President of Germany or the Chancellor request it (Basic Law, Article 39.3).
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The most important organisational structures within the Bundestag are 'factions' (*Fraktionen*; sing.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] A parliamentary faction must consist of at least 5% of all members of parliament.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Members of parliament from different parties may only join in a faction if those parties did not run against each other in any German state during the election.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Normally, all parties that surpassed the 5%-threshold build a faction of their own.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The CDU and CSU however, have always formed a joint faction, called CDU/CSU or Union.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] This is possible, as the CSU only runs in the state of Bavaria and the CDU only runs in the other 15 states.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The size of a faction determines the extent of its representation on committees, the time slots allotted for speaking, the number of committee chairs it can hold, and its representation in executive bodies of the Bundestag.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The factions, not the members, receive the bulk of government funding for legislative and administrative activities.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The leadership of each *Fraktion* consists of a parliamentary party leader, several deputy leaders, and an executive committee.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The leadership's major responsibilities are to represent the *Fraktion*, enforce party discipline and orchestrate the party's parliamentary activities.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The members of each *Fraktion* are distributed among working groups focused on specific policy-related topics such as social policy, economics, and foreign policy.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The *Fraktion* meets every Tuesday afternoon in the weeks in which the Bundestag is in session to consider legislation before the Bundestag and formulate the party's position on it.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Parties that do not hold 5% of the Bundestag-seats may be granted the status of a *group* in the Bundestag; this is decided case by case, as the rules of procedure do not state a fixed number of seats for this.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] This status entails some privileges which are in general less than those of a faction.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Most of the legislative work in the Bundestag is the product of standing committees, which exist largely unchanged throughout one legislative period.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The number of committees approximates the number of federal ministries, and the titles of each are roughly similar (e.g., defense, agriculture, and labor).
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] There are, as of the current nineteenth Bundestag, 24 standing committees.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The distribution of committee chairs and the membership of each committee reflect the relative strength of the various Parliamentary groups in the chamber.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] In the current nineteenth Bundestag, the CDU/CSU chaired ten committees, the SPD five, the AfD and the FDP three each, The Left and the Greens two each.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Members of the opposition party can chair a significant number of standing committees (e.g. the Budget Committee of the Bundestag was by tradition chaired by the biggest opposition party, until the 21st Bundestag, when Alternative for Germany was denied this post).
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] These committees have either a small staff or no staff at all.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The members of Bundestag and the presidium are supported by the Bundestag Administration.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] It is headed by the Director, that reports to the President of the Bundestag.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The Bundestag Administrations four departments are Parliament Service, Research, Information / Documentation and Central Affairs.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The Bundestag Administration employs around 3,000 employees.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Also following the tradition of German diets, the German Bundestag can legally convene on any location, domestic and foreign.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The Reichstag plenary chamber is not determined by law as the location of the assembly, making it a facility of convenience.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Bundestag's predecessor, the German Reichstag, convened in the Kroll Opera House in Berlin, after the Reichstag with its then wooden interior and walls burned down in the Reichstag fire.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] After World War II, the Bundestag did not have own facilities to call home and had to convene in the Bundeshaus in Bonn together with the Bundesrat.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] 1953, the plenary chambers in the Bundeshaus had to be expanded and the Bundestag assembled in a radio building in Cologne.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Until 1965, the Bundestag assembled in West Berlin for nine sessions.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Seven sessions have been held in the Technische Universität Berlin and two sessions in Berlin's Congress Hall in Tiergarten.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The assemblies met severe protest from the communist side, the last session even interrupted by Soviet aircraft in supersonic low-altitude flight.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] 1971, the four occupying powers agreed to not accept Bundestag assemblies in West Berlin anymore.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The Bundestag assembled in the Old Waterworks Building in Bonn when the old plenary chamber had to get broken down, and in the new plenary chamber for only a few years after Germany's reunification.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The most distinctive assembly of the Bundestag outside its regular chambers was on 4 October 1990, the day after German reunification.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] The Bundestag assembled inside the Reichstag building in Berlin for the first time after 57 years, and remote from its then-regular home in Bonn.
[src:alois-mertes/bundestag] Soon after this most memorable assembly, the Bundestag decided to move from Bonn back to Berlin by a law which sets only the city of Berlin to be the home of the Bundestag, not the building.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] The CSU contests elections only in Bavaria, while the CDU operates in the other 15 states of Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] The CSU also reflects the particular concerns of the largely rural, Catholic south.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] According to German Federal Electoral Law, members of a parliamentary group which share the same basic political aims must not compete with one another in any federal state.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] The parties themselves officially remain completely independent with their own leadership and only few issue- or age-based joint organisations, which makes the alliance informal.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] However, in practice the committees of the parties harmonise their decisions with each other and the two parties run behind a common candidate for Chancellor, and the leader of one party is usually invited to party conventions of the other party.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Both the CDU and CSU are members of the European People's Party and the International Democracy Union.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Both parties sit in the European People's Party Group in the European Parliament.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] The CDU and CSU share a common youth organisation, the Young Union, a common pupil organisation, the Pupil Union of Germany, a common student organisation, the Association of Christian Democratic Students and a common *Mittelstand* organisation, the Mittelstand and Business association.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Both the CDU and the CSU were established after World War II and share a perspective based on Christian democracy and conservatism and hold the dominant centre-right position in the German political spectrum.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] However the CDU's foundation was the result of a major re-organisation of the centre-right political camp compared to the Weimar Republic.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] The BVP became the sister party of the DZP and they did not compete against each other except for the May 1924 German federal election, the 1924 Bavarian state election and the 1925 German presidential election.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] The DZP and BVP were mostly jointly represented at the Imperial governments.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Alliance for Germany was a coalition for the 1990 East German general election consisting of the CDU, the DSU and Democratic Awakening which merged into the CDU.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] During the 1970s and then again after 2015, several CSU leaders have expressed the wish to make the CSU a truly independent party without formal ties to the CDU.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Usually they combined this wish with an expansion to the rest of Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] After 1969, CDU and CSU were in the opposition in the Bundestag.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] CDU leader Kohl wanted to win the liberal FDP again for a coalition with the CDU/CSU, while the CSU leader Strauß had different plans.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] He aimed for a right wing majority without the FDP.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Additionally, Strauß thought little of the current CDU leader Kohl, a more moderate Christian Democrat.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Strauß believed that CDU and CSU should be separate national parties to address different audience: the CDU the moderate, social and liberal voters, the CSU the conservative voters.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] After the elections they should still form a government together.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] In 1975, the federal CDU declared Kohl to be the next CDU/CSU chancellor candidate for the 1976 general elections – without consulting the CSU.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Kohl did well in the elections on 3 October 1976, although Social Democrats and FDP had still enough seats to continue their coalition.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Kohl decided to leave his post as prime minister of the state of Rhineland-Palatinate for the chairmanship of the CDU/CSU Bundestag faction.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] In November that year, the 49 CSU Bundestag members gathered in the party's educational centre in Wildbad Kreuth, Southern Bavaria.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] 30 of them voted for a proposal to form a CSU Bundestag parliamentary group of its own.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] CDU leader Kohl was informed only later via the media.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] This 'Kreuth separation decision' *(Kreuther Trennungsbeschluss)* was a major political earthquake and caused the CDU to react swiftly and resolutely.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Kohl threatened the CSU by preparing the creation of a CDU party organization in Bavaria.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] In March 1977, the *CDU Bayern* was supposed to be founded in Nuremberg.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] On 12 December 1976, the vote was rescinded after the CDU had threatened in turn to form local associations within Bavaria and to run in Bavarian elections against the CSU.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] It turned out that most local CSU leaders and also conservative CDU state leaders did not approve a separation between CSU and CDU.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] The CSU Bundestag members revoked their decision.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] On 7 December, the CDU/CSU Bundestag group elected Kohl as its chairman.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] In 1980, Strauß was the joint CDU/CSU chancellor candidate and lost more than 4 percent of the votes.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] This ended his ambitions for a federal CSU.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Under the chairmanship of Angela Merkel (2000–2018), the CDU abandoned some right wing positions and shifted more to the political centre.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Especially the 2015 refugee crisis divided the German population and caused conflict between the CDU and the CSU.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Therefore, a federal CSU was discussed again among party members and journalists.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] For example, conservative *Welt* columnist Ansgar Graw wrote in 2016 that CDU and CSU lost its stance as a law and order party.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] As Merkel's CDU could not move to the right without losing credibility, Graw called the CSU to become a federal party, a right wing party that rigorously deports asylum seekers without right to stay.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] On the contrary, former CSU leader Theo Waigel warned against a separate election campaign, claiming that if this happened, the CDU and CSU would fight each other much more than the rest of the parties.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] In 2018, Interior Minister Horst Seehofer, a former Minister-President of Bavaria and the leader of the CSU, opposed CDU Chancellor Angela Merkel's policy on Syrian refugees in Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Seehofer hoped to place restrictions on incoming refugees, many of whom enter the country through Bavaria.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] His stance was seen as being in part motivated by the 2018 Bavarian state election in which it was feared that the far-right Alternative for Germany would make gains.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] In June 2018, CDU and CSU Bundestag members held separate meetings on the topic of refugees, which was highly unusual.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] A fake Twitter account announced that CSU leader Seehofer had abolished the CDU/CSU alliance and that CDU vice chair Bouffier had called for a CDU in Bavaria.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Many journalists published the news, which was interpreted by the *Münchner Merkur* as a sign that such events are considered no longer absurd or unlikely.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Political scientist Heinrich Oberreuter did not believe in Seehofer's threat to expand the CSU to the rest of Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Both parties aim essentially for the same voters.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] As separate parties in the general elections both would lose voters.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] The CSU would lose its unique selling point as a Bavarian party.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] With a CDU in Bavaria, the CSU would fall from 47 to 30 percent in Bavaria.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] A federal CSU was again discussed prior to the general elections of 2021.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] CSU leader Markus Söder was unhappy about the CDU decision to declare CDU leader Armin Laschet the chancellor candidate and successor of Angela Merkel.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] In September 2020, the CSU created online memberships for people not living in Bavaria.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] A survey in May 2021 foresaw that a federal CSU may win at least 9 percent of the votes, especially in Eastern Germany and among FDP voters.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Both parties suffered heavy losses in elections after 2017.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] In the Bavarian state elections of October 2018, the CSU lost 10.5 percent.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] With 37.2 percent, this was its worst election result since 1950.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] In the federal elections of 2021, the CDU lost 7.9 percent and the CSU 1.0 percent of the (party list) votes.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Following the federal election which was held on February 23, 2025, the CDU was projected to recapture the most seats in the German parliament, with the CDU/CSU alliance expected to return to power.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] CDU leader Friedrich Merz will most likely serve as the German chancellor.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] The CDU and the CSU usually only differ slightly in their political stances.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] The CSU is usually considered more socially conservative (especially on family issues, e.g. the CSU favors providing infants' parents with compensation (Betreuungsgeld) if they intend not to use the public day nursery system to work while the CDU favors public funding of day nurseries).
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] The CSU government in Bavaria has implemented one of the strictest regulations for shopping hours in Germany in order to protect employees.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] The CSU also strongly opposed ideas of an income unrelated system of contributions to public health insurances, a proposal which met a lot of approval in the CDU in 2010.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] CSU politicians often make their mark as self-declared defenders of Bavaria's state rights and cultural independence from federal or European Union bureaucrats, even in times of conservative federal governments or conservative presidents of the European Commission.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] In 1998, then-Chancellor Helmut Kohl of the CDU had to pressure the CSU intensely not to veto the introduction of the euro as the new currency in Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] On the other hand, the name euro was the idea of former CSU chairman Theo Waigel, who served as finance minister when the euro was introduced and held a very pro-European position in contrast to the Bavarian government of Edmund Stoiber.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Since 2016, the CSU has strongly been advocating the idea of a maximum number (Obergrenze) of 200,000 people per year to limit the number of asylum seekers.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] This is opposed by the CDU because they claim that it is impossible to limit the number through border control.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] While both parties officially identify themselves as non-denominational Christian, the Catholic influence on the CSU is stronger than that on the CDU since Bavaria is predominantly Catholic while Christians in Germany as a whole are approximately equally balanced between Catholics and Protestants.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] There are nevertheless strong regional differences within Bavaria and Germany as a whole with large predominantly Protestant areas in northern Bavaria and large predominantly Catholic areas in North Rhine-Westphalia and South Western Germany having a strong effect on CDU state politicians.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Saarland's former CDU Minister-President Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer heavily opposed same-sex marriages in July 2017 while the CDU in Schleswig-Holstein was in favor, with Saarland having the largest share of Catholic Christians in any German state.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] CDU and CSU are two separate parties with separate organization.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] While the CDU is a federal party with members and local affiliations in 15 of the 16 German states, the CSU has members and affiliations only in Bavaria.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] (CSU online members live outside of Bavaria but have no vote within the party.) Also, the CDU runs only in regional and local elections outside of Bavaria.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Both parties do have party lists for the general (federal) elections to the Bundestag: the CDU has 15 lists in each of the 15 non-Bavarian states, the CSU only in Bavaria.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Since 1972, both parties agreed a joint election manifesto for the federal elections.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Sometimes the CSU additionally published a manifesto of its own.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Both parties always gather behind a joint candidate for the chancellorship.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] There is no approved procedure to select this candidate, creating tensions between both parties from time to time.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] During the federal campaign, the CSU may decide to present mainly Bavarian candidates on the election posters and not the CDU joint chancellor candidate, and the popular candidates of the CDU may decide not to show up in the Bavarian campaign.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Both parties together form a parliamentary group (*Fraktion*) in the Bundestag.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Such a *Fraktionsgemeinschaft* is legal because both parties do not compete with each other during elections (the voters can nowhere decide between a CDU and a CSU candidate).
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] The *Fraktionsgemeinschaft* (parliamentary group alliance) works on the basis of a *Fraktionsvertrag* (parliamentary group agreement) with some special provisions for the CSU, e.g. with regard to speaking time in the Bundestag.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] The parliamentary group has one chair and several vice chairs (12 in the 2021 Bundestag).
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] The First Deputy chair is *ex officio* the leader of the *CSU-Landesgruppe*.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] The *Fraktion* is divided into 16 *Landesgruppen* (state groups), comprising the *Fraktion* members per state.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] The *CSU-Landesgruppenchef* is considered one of the most prolific members of the Bundestag parliamentary group.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Historically, most of these politicians have become members of the federal government.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] CDU and CSU always take part in coalition negotiations together, although they behave like two different parties.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] Both parties join a federal government coalition together; there has never been only one of them in government.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] At least one major government department is 'given' to the CSU.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] In the past, the CSU often lead the departments for postal services (when this ministry still existed), transportation, constructions, or agriculture.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] In European elections, CDU and CSU have separate party lists.
[src:alois-mertes/cdu-csu] In the European Parliament, they form a group within the parliamentary group of the European People's Party.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The **chancellor of Germany**, officially the **federal chancellor of the Federal Republic of Germany**, is the head of government of Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The chancellor is elected by the Bundestag on the proposal of the federal president and without debate (Article 63 of the German Constitution).
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] During a state of defence declared by the Bundestag the chancellor also assumes the position of commander-in-chief of the Bundeswehr.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Ten people (nine men and one woman) have served as chancellor of the Federal Republic of Germany, the first being Konrad Adenauer from 1949 to 1963.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] (Another 26 men had served as "Reich chancellors" of the previous German Empire from 1871 to 1945.) The current officeholder is Friedrich Merz of the Christian Democratic Union, sworn in on 6 May 2025.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The office of chancellor has a long history, stemming back to the Holy Roman Empire (c.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The title of chancellor (Latin: *cancellarius*) was given to the head of the clerics at the Imperial chapel.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The chapel's college acted as the emperor's chancery issuing deeds and capitularies.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Eventually, the office of imperial archchancellor was given to the archbishops of Mainz.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] In 1559, Emperor Ferdinand I established the agency of an imperial chancellery (*Reichshofkanzlei*) at the Hofburg Palace in Vienna, headed by a vice chancellor under the nominal authority of the archbishop of Mainz.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Upon the 1620 Battle of White Mountain, Emperor Ferdinand II created the office of court chancellor for the Archduchy of Austria.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] This office was in charge of the internal and foreign affairs of the Habsburg monarchy.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] From May 1753 to August 1792, the office of an Austrian state chancellor was held by Prince Kaunitz.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The imperial chancellery lost its importance, and from the days of Queen Maria Theresa and Holy Roman emperor Joseph II, merely existed on paper.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] After the 1806 dissolution of the Holy Roman Empire by Napoleon, Prince Klemens von Metternich served as state chancellor of the Austrian Empire.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Likewise Prince Karl August von Hardenberg acted as chancellor of the Kingdom of Prussia (1810–1822).
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] At the conclusion of the Napoleonic Wars, the Congress of Vienna established the German Confederation as a replacement for the Holy Roman Empire, but this organisation did not have a government or legislature, only the Bundestag that represented the member states.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The modern office of chancellor was established with the beginning of the North German Confederation in 1867, after the Prussian Army's decisive victory in the brief Austro-Prussian War of 1866 over the rival Austrian Empire.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Unlike its predecessor the German Confederation, the North German Confederation did have an office of *Bundeskanzler* (federal Chancellor), which was given to the Minister-President of Prussia Otto von Bismarck.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] In 1871 the North German Confederation transformed into the German Empire, with the federal chancellor becoming *Reichskanzler* (imperial chancellor).
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The office of *Reichskanzler* continued during the Weimar Republic (1918–1933).
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] In Nazi Germany the office of *Reichskanzler* was never formally abolished, but instead combined with the office of *Reichspräsident*.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] On 1 August 1934, the day before Reichspräsident Paul von Hindenburg's death, the Hitler cabinet passed a law merging the offices of Reich Chancellor and Reich President in the person of Hitler.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] This law came into force upon Hindenburg's death.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] In May 1949, four years after the End of World War II in Europe, the Basic Law of the Federal Republic of Germany, aka West Germany, revived the office of *Bundeskanzler*.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The reunification of Germany (3 October 1990) continued the Basic Law of the Federal Republic for the reunited German state, including the office of chancellor.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The role of chancellor has varied during different eras.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] From 1867 to 1918, the chancellor was the only responsible minister at the federal level.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] He was appointed by the *Bundespräsidium*, (i.e. the King of Prussia; the Emperor of Germany from 1871).
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The state secretaries (*Staatssekretäre*) were civil servants subordinate to the chancellor and similar to ministers.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Besides his executive duties, the constitution gave the chancellor only one function: presiding over the Bundesrat (Federal Council), the representative organ of the various German states.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The chancellor was also nearly always Minister President of Prussia, which was the largest and dominant state in the Empire.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Indirectly, this gave him the power of the Bundesrat, including to dissolve the parliament and call for elections.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Although effective government was possible only in cooperation with the Reichstag, the results of the elections had at most an indirect influence on the chancellorship.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] By October 1918 on the verge of disastrous defeat in the First World War, was the Empire's 1871 constitution changed and reformed, to require that the chancellor have the confidence of parliament (as in the UK House of Commons and other European parliamentary democracies).
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] On 9 November 1918, Chancellor Max von Baden declared the abdication of the emperor Wilhelm II without having been authorized to do so by Wilhelm.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Wilhelm had left Berlin on 29 October to travel to Spa, Belgium where the Oberste Heeresleitung resided.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] On 10 November, one day after the republic in Germany had been proclamated, Wilhelm fled to the Netherlands and asked for asylum (that Queen Wilhelinma granted him two days later).
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] At the end of November 1918, his wife emperess Auguste Victoria left Berlin and travelled to the Netherlands.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Following the defeat a new post-war democratic Republican government was set up by the popularly elected Weimar National Assembly, which met in Weimar (Thuringia in 1919/20.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] According to the Weimar constitution, the chancellor was head of a collegial democratic government.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The chancellor was appointed by the new president of Germany (Reich President), as were the subordinate ministers of various portfolios (departments / agencies) on the chancellor's recommendation.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The chancellor or any minister had to be dismissed if Reichstag demanded it.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] As today, the chancellor had the prerogative to determine the policy direction of his government.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] In reality this power was limited by the needs of coalition governments of the several major political parties (and numerous smaller minor ones) plus the powers of the Reich President.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Cabinet decisions were taken by majority vote.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Under the circumstances, much like his French counterpart, the Weimar-era chancellor was as much the chairman of the cabinet as he was its leader.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] On 30 January 1933 (seizure of power day), Adolf Hitler of the Nazi Party, the biggest party in parliament, was appointed chancellor by President Paul von Hindenburg.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Subsequently, the 1919 Weimar Constitution was *de facto* set aside.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] After Hindenburg's death on 2 August 1934, Hitler arrogated to himself the powers of the president.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] He chose the official title *Führer und Reichskanzler* (meaning "Leader and Chancellor of the Reich").
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The 1949 constitution gave the chancellor greater powers than during the Weimar Republic of the 1920s and early 1930s, while strongly diminishing the role of the president of Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Germany has often been referred to as a "chancellor democracy", reflecting the role of the chancellor as Germany's chief executive.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Since 1867, over 30 people have served as chancellor of the North German Confederation, the German Empire, the Weimar Republic, Nazi Germany, West Germany and the current Federal Republic of Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] In communist East Germany (1949–1990), the position of chancellor did not exist.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The North German Confederation was created on 1 July 1867.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] According to the constitution of this federal state, the king of Prussia served as *Bundespräsidium* (in fact a head of state) and appointed a *Bundeskanzler*.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] This chancellor was the only member of the executive, the only responsible minister.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] A law could only pass with the consent of both organs.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The federal council was not considered to be a parliament or parliament chamber, as its members were not elected for a fixed period of time, but appointed representatives of the states' governments.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Though, the two organs can also be described as *upper house* and *lower house* since they shared the task of legislation.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] After the south German states had joined the federal state in 1870/71, during the war against France, the North German Confederation transformed into the *Deutsches Reich* or German Empire.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] At this occasion, the term *Bundeskanzler* was recoined as *Reichskanzler*, and the king of Prussia was given the title of emperor additionally.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The political system remained largely the same.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Otto von Bismarck was (from 1862) Prime Minister of Prussia, the largest state in the Confederation.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] He retained this office and used it to set up the new federal state; he was not interested in a fully developed federal executive with cabinet ministers acting independently.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] But Bismarck also had another reason to remain Prime Minister of Prussia.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] According to the constitution, the chancellor was only a federal minister and presided over the Bundesrat.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] As chancellor, his powers were limited because he could not introduce bills, speak in parliament or dismiss parliament (which the Prussian government could do in Prussia, for example).
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] As chairman of the Bundesrat, he had no voting rights.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Through this bundling of offices, chancellor Bismarck used the power of the federal council to govern.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] As a member of the federal council, he had speaking rights in the parliament.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] He de facto introduced draft bills into the legislative process.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Thanks to the federal council he could, with the approval of the emperor, dismiss parliament and call for new elections.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Likewise, most of Bismarck's successors were chancellor and prime minister at the same time, although the constitution never asked for this combination.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] In 1878, a new law *(Stellvertretungsgesetz)* installed the office of *Staatssekretär*.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The chancellor was given the opportunity to formally install state secretaries to represent him and sign for him *(contraseign)*.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The chancellor, though, could overrule any of them any time.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The office of State Secretary did not formally evolve into a cabinet minister.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] In practice, however, state secretaries acted in a similar way to ministers in other countries.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The constitution of the German Empire was reformed on 29 October 1918, when the parliament *(Reichstag)* was given the right to dismiss the chancellor.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The reform was obviously too little too late to prevent the outbreak of revolution (Kiel mutiny) on 3 November 1918.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] On 9 November 1918, chancellor Prince Maximilian of Baden handed over his office of chancellor to the leader of the Majority Social Democrats, Friedrich Ebert.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] During that time, Ebert also served as chairman of the "Council of the People's Deputies", until on 29 December 1918 together with the allied Independent Social Democrat party leader Hugo Haase.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] This council de facto took over the roles of emperor, parliament and federal council.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The council called for the election of a constituent assembly on 19 January 1919.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The constitution stipulated that the president appoint and dismiss the chancellor and ministers.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The ministers were appointed by the president on the recommendation of the chancellor (Article 53), and members of the government required the confidence of the Reichstag (Article 54).
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The provisions gave rise to the question of who in fact was responsible for forming the government.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Constitutional law expert Ernst Rudolf Huber said that the constitution had tacitly assumed that the president would have discussions with party leaders in the Reichstag before he made ministerial appointments.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Based on these talks, the president would get a sense of which potential chancellor would be able to build a stable majority in the Reichstag.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] According to the sense of the Weimar Constitution, the president was thus to have the initiative.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The task of putting together the Reich government was nevertheless the responsibility of the chancellor.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The president could not appoint anyone as minister whom the chancellor had not proposed.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The chancellor alone had to answer to the Reichstag and the president for the policy guidelines, and he determined whether the conduct of business by the individual Reich ministries conformed to the guidelines.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The government's decisions required a majority vote of the ministers, who sitting together were known as the National Ministry (Article 58).
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The chancellor could therefore be outvoted, as could a department minister.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The chancellor presided over the government, and he had to conduct business in accordance with given rules of procedure.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] In practice the Reich chancellor's power to determine political guidelines was limited by his own party as well as the other parties in the governing coalition.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The Weimar chancellors were accordingly men whose strength lay in mediation rather than political initiative.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Constitutionally, there was also the fact that the president had certain special rights.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The actions of the president required the countersignature of the chancellor or the minister or ministers concerned, but the president always had to be informed about matters of foreign and defence policy.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The Reichstag could call for the dismissal of any member of the government, including the chancellor.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Under Articles 54 and 59, the Reichstag could also impeach the chancellor as well as the ministers and the president before the State Court for the German Reich (*Staatsgerichtshof für das Deutsche Reich*), the Weimar Republic's constitutional court.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Adolf Hitler was appointed chancellor of Germany on 30 January 1933 by Paul von Hindenburg.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] On taking office, Hitler immediately began accumulating power and changing the nature of the chancellorship.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] After only two months in office, and following the burning of the Reichstag building, the parliament passed the Enabling Act giving the chancellor full legislative powers for a period of four years – the cabinet could introduce any law without consent of parliament.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Technically, however, Hindenburg was able to dismiss the chancellor.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] On 1 August 1934, when Hindenburg was already ill and expected to die in the near future, Hitler used the Enabling Act to pass a new law, which came into force one day later.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] This law on the head of state stated that the offices of Reich chancellor and Reich president would "merge" and that the powers of the Reich president would be transferred to the "Leader and Reich Chancellor Adolf Hitler".
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] This can be interpreted as the abolition of the office of president; a president had to be elected every seven years, which was not in Hitler's interests.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Hindenburg died on the same day, 2 August 1934.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] In April 1945, Hitler gave instruction that upon his death, the office of the *Führer* would dissolve and be replaced by the previous system of administration: that of the office of the president separate from that of chancellor.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] On 30 April 1945, when Hitler committed suicide, he was briefly succeeded as Chancellor by Joseph Goebbels and as President of Germany by Grand Admiral Karl Dönitz.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] When Goebbels also committed suicide, Dönitz did not appoint a successor as Chancellor, instead appointing Count Schwerin von Krosigk as head of government with the title "Leading Minister".
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The 1949 German constitution, the Basic Law (*Grundgesetz*), invests the chancellor (German, *Bundeskanzler*) with broad powers to initiate government policy.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] For that reason, some observers refer to the German political system as a "chancellor democracy".
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Whichever major party (historically, CDU/CSU or SPD) does not hold the chancellorship usually calls its leading candidate for the federal election "chancellor-candidate" (*Kanzlerkandidat*).
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The federal government (*Bundesregierung*) consists of the chancellor and cabinet ministers.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The chancellor's authority emanates from the provisions of the Basic Law and in practice from their status as leader of the party (or coalition of parties) holding a majority of seats in the *Bundestag* (federal parliament).
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] With the exception of Helmut Schmidt and Olaf Scholz, the chancellor has also been chairman of their own party.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] This was the case with Chancellor Gerhard Schröder from 1999 until he resigned the chairmanship of the SPD in 2004.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The first chancellor, Konrad Adenauer, set many precedents that continue today and established the chancellorship as the clear focus of power in Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Under the provisions of the Basic Law giving him the power to set guidelines for all fields of policy, Adenauer arrogated nearly all major decisions to himself.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] He often treated his ministers as mere extensions of his authority rather than colleagues.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] While his successors have tended to be less domineering, the chancellor has acquired enough *ex officio* authority (in addition to their constitutional powers) that Germany is often described by constitutional law experts as a "chancellor democracy".
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The chancellor determines the composition of the Federal Cabinet.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The president formally appoints and dismisses cabinet ministers, on the recommendation of the chancellor; no parliamentary approval is needed.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] According to the Basic Law, the chancellor may set the number of cabinet ministers and dictate their specific duties.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Chancellor Ludwig Erhard had the largest cabinet, with 22 ministers, in the mid-1960s.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Helmut Kohl presided over 17 ministers at the start of his fourth term in 1994; the 2002 cabinet, the second of Chancellor Gerhard Schröder, had 13 ministers, and the Angela Merkel cabinet as of 22 November 2005 had 15.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] This can be done by means of a regular election of the chancellor or by a constructive vote of no confidence.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] A regular **chancellor's election** is necessary whenever the office of chancellor has fallen vacant.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The chancellor's election is one of the few cases in which a vote in the Bundestag requires a majority of all elected members, not just a majority of those assembled at the time, or the so-called *Kanzlermehrheit* ("chancellor majority").
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Since the electoral reform of 2023, which was first implemented in the 2025 election, the number of members of the Bundestag has been set at 630, meaning that the majority required to elect a chancellor is always 316 votes.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The regular election of the Chancellor is described in Article 63 of the Basic Law and can extend over up to three election phases.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Another possibility to vote a new chancellor into office is the constructive vote of no confidence, which allows the Bundestag to replace a sitting chancellor via a motion of no-confidence, if it elects a new chancellor with the "chancellor-majority" at the same time (see "Confidence", below).
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Of the two constructive votes of no confidence tabled in the history of the Federal Republic, one failed (Rainer Barzel against Willy Brandt in 1972), while one was successful (Helmut Kohl against Helmut Schmidt in 1982).
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] In principle, the Chancellor is dependent on the confidence of Parliament, which is bestowed upon him with the election.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] This is to be distinguished from a motion of confidence.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] This is a motion that only the Chancellor can submit to the Bundestag (optionally in conjunction with another motion or bill) to the effect that the Bundestag explicitly expresses its confidence in him (again).
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The legislative emergency is limited to six months after declaration and can only be declared once during the Bundeskanzler's term of office.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] In practice, however, the motion of confidence has also established itself as a means for the chancellor to deliberately trigger new elections by submitting the motion of confidence with the explicit goal of losing the vote and then requesting a dissolution of parliament.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] A total of six times a chancellor has submitted a motion of confidence to date; only twice was it a "genuine motion of confidence" (1982 and 2001), while in four cases the respective chancellor had the goal of triggering a snap election from the outset (1972, 1982, 2005, 2024).
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The chancellor must appoint one of the cabinet ministers as vice chancellor (Article 69.1 Basic Law).
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The vice chancellor may deputise for the chancellor, if they are absent or unable to perform their duties.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Although the chancellor is theoretically free to choose any cabinet minister, in coalition governments the leadership of the second biggest coalition party usually designates one of their ministers for the position, whom the chancellor appoints accordingly.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] If the chancellor's term in office ends or if they resign, the Bundestag has to elect a new chancellor.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The president of Germany may ask the former chancellor to act as chancellor until a new office holder is elected, but if they are unwilling or unable to do so, the president may also appoint the vice chancellor as acting chancellor.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] This has happened once: On 7 May 1974, Chancellor Willy Brandt resigned as a consequence of the Guillaume affair, an espionage scandal.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] In his letter of resignation to President Gustav Heinemann he requested, to be not asked to remain in office in an acting capacity and instead to appoint the vice chancellor as acting chancellor.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] President Heinemann followed the request.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Vice Chancellor Walter Scheel was appointed acting chancellor and served for nine days until the election of Helmut Schmidt on 16 May 1974.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Scheel not taken into account, three persons, Ludwig Erhard, Willy Brandt, and Olaf Scholz, have held both the office of Vice Chancellor and that of Chancellor of Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The current vice chancellor of Germany is Lars Klingbeil, who also serves as Minister of Finance in the Merz cabinet.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Since 2001, the official seat of the chancellor is the Federal Chancellery in Berlin (*Bundeskanzleramt*).
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The former seat of the Federal Chancellery, the Palais Schaumburg in the former capital Bonn, now serves as a secondary official seat.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The chancellor's country retreat is Schloss Meseberg in the state of Brandenburg.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The private lodging of the chancellors at Bonn has previously been the *chancellor's bungalow* built by Ludwig Erhard in the park of Palais Schaumburg, while his predecessor Konrad Adenauer used to live in his private house near Bonn.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Under Adenauer, the government had also acquired a villa in Dahlem in 1962, a suburban district of southwestern Berlin, as a *pied-a-terre* of the chancellors in West-Berlin.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Gerhard Schröder lived there between 1999 and 2001.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Since 2004 it has however served as a private residence for the presidents of Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Angela Merkel preferred to live with her husband in her private apartment downtown.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] The correct style of address in German is *Herr Bundeskanzler* (male) or *Frau Bundeskanzlerin* (female).
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] In international correspondence, the chancellor is referred to as "His/Her Excellency the Chancellor of the Federal Republic of Germany" ("*Seine/Ihre Exzellenz der Bundeskanzler/die Bundeskanzlerin der Bundesrepublik Deutschland*").
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] Holding the third-highest state office available within Germany, the chancellor of Germany receives €220,000 per annum and a €22,000 bonus, i.e. one and two thirds of Salary Grade B11 (according to § 11 (1) a of the Federal Law on Ministers – *Bundesministergesetz*, BGBl.
[src:alois-mertes/chancellor-of-germany] 1166 and attachment IV to the Federal Law on Salaries of Officers – *Bundesbesoldungsgesetz*, BGBl.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] They have developed in parallel in the 1940s, act on federal level as "the Union" CDU/CSU, but have never merged.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] CDU is the major party of the centre-right in German politics.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Friedrich Merz has been federal chairman of the CDU since 31 January 2022, and has served as the Chancellor of Germany since 6 May 2025.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CDU/CSU is the largest faction in the 21st Bundestag, the current German federal legislature, with 208 (164 CDU + 44 CSU) out of 630 seats, having won a combined 28.5% (22.6% CDU and 6.0% CSU) of votes in the 2025 federal election.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The group's parliamentary leader has been Jens Spahn since 5 May 2025.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Founded in 1945 as an interdenominational Christian party, the CDU effectively succeeded the traditional Catholic Centre Party that was active from 1870 until 1933.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] When political parties were allowed in Allied-occupied Germany, many former Centre members joined the all-Christian CDU, including its first leader Konrad Adenauer.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The party also included politicians of other backgrounds, including liberals and conservatives.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] As a result, the party claims to represent "Christian-social, liberal and conservative" elements.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CDU is generally pro-European in outlook.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Black, associated with Christian clerical robes like cassock/soutane, is the party's customary and historical electoral color, used in many polls and other publications.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Since the change in the CDU corporate design in 2023, the font of their logo was changed from red to black.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The logo is on a white frame and always connected with the Flag of Germany black-red-gold *upswing*.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Two of the others preferred CDU colors are named after places where Konrad Adenauer had lived, Cadenabbia-Turquoise, dark Rhöndorf-Blue, plus White and Union-Gold.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CDU leads the federal government in a grand coalition with the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD), after returning as the largest party in the 2025 federal election.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Germany's three longest-serving post-war Chancellors have all come from the CDU, specifically: Helmut Kohl (1982–1998), Angela Merkel (2005–2021), and Konrad Adenauer (1949–1963).
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The party also currently leads the governments of seven of Germany's sixteen states.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CDU is a member of the Centrist Democrat International, the International Democracy Union, and the European People's Party (EPP).
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] It is the largest party in the EPP with 23 MEPs.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Ursula von der Leyen, the current President of the European Commission, is also a member of the CDU.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] 1949 election poster of the CDU reading "We cannot do magic — but we can work/do our job.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Immediately following the end of World War II and the foreign occupation of Germany, simultaneous yet unrelated meetings began occurring throughout the country, each with the intention of planning a Christian-democratic party.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Consequently, the CDU was established in Berlin on 26 June 1945 and in Rheinland and Westfalen in September of the same year.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The result of these meetings was the establishment of an inter-confessional (Catholic and Protestant alike) party influenced heavily by the political tradition of liberal conservatism.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CDU experienced considerable success gaining widespread support from the time of its creation in Berlin on 26 June 1945 until its first convention on 21 October 1950, at which future West German Chancellor Konrad Adenauer was named the first Chairman of the party.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The latter was more nationalist and sought German reunification even at the expense of concessions to the Soviet Union (USSR), depicting Adenauer as an instrument of both the Americans and the Vatican.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The Western powers appreciated the CDU's right-ward slant, its commitment to capitalism, and its value as a pivotal oppositional force to the communists, thereby keeping consistent with US/UK foreign policy.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] In addition, Adenauer was also trusted by the British.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] However, the party was split over issues of rearmament within the Western alliance and German unification as a neutral state.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Adenauer staunchly defended his pro-Western position and outmaneuvered some of his opponents.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] He also refused to consider the SPD as a party of the coalition until he felt sure that they shared his anti-communist position.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Therefore, the CDU was the dominant political party for the first two decades following the establishment of West Germany in 1949.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Adenauer remained the party's leader until 1963, when former Minister of Economics Ludwig Erhard replaced him.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] As the Free Democratic Party (FDP) withdrew from the governing coalition in 1966 due to disagreements over fiscal and economic policy, Erhard was forced to resign.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Consequently, a grand coalition with the SPD took over government under CDU Chancellor Kurt Georg Kiesinger.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The SPD quickly gained popularity and succeeded in forming a social-liberal coalition with the FDP following the 1969 federal election, forcing the CDU out of power for the first time in its history.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The Union parties had close ties with the *Heimatvertriebene* associations (Germans who fled or were expelled from the eastern territories) who hoped for a return of or in these territories.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Seven Bundestag members, including former vice chancellor Erich Mende, defected from the FDP and SPD to the CDU in protest against these treaties, depriving Brandt of his majority, and providing a thin majority for the CDU and CSU.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] In April 1972, the CDU saw its chance to return to power, calling a constructive vote of no confidence.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] CDU chairman Rainer Barzel was almost certain to become the new Chancellor.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] But not all parliamentarians voted as expected (it was later revealed that two CDU/CSU deputies had been bribed by the East German Stasi): Brandt won the vote and stayed in office.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Thus, the CDU continued its role as opposition for a total of thirteen years.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] In 1982, the FDP withdrew from the coalition with the SPD and allowed the CDU to regain power.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] CDU Chairman Helmut Kohl became the new Chancellor of West Germany and his CDU/CSU–FDP coalition was confirmed in the 1983 federal election.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] After the collapse of the East German government in 1989, Kohl—supported by the governments of the United States and reluctantly by those of France and the United Kingdom—called for German reunification.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] On 3 October 1990, the government of East Germany was abolished and its territory acceded to the territory of the Basic Law already in place in West Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The East German CDU merged with its West German counterpart and elections were held for the reunified country.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Public support for the coalition's work in the process of German reunification was reiterated in the 1990 federal election in which the CDU–FDP governing coalition experienced a clear victory.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Although Kohl was re-elected, the party began losing much of its popularity because of an economic recession in the former GDR and increased taxes in the west.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CDU was nonetheless able to win the 1994 federal election by a narrow margin thanks to an economic recovery.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Kohl served as chairman until the party's electoral defeat in 1998, when he was succeeded by Wolfgang Schäuble.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] In the 1998 federal election, the CDU polled 28.4% and the CSU 6.7% of the national vote, the lowest result for those parties since 1949; a red–green coalition under the leadership of Gerhard Schröder took power until 2005.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Schäuble resigned in early 2000 as a result of a party financing scandal and was replaced by Angela Merkel, the first woman and the first person from East Germany to lead the federal party.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] She remained the leader of the CDU for more than eighteen years.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] In the 2002 federal election, Merkel ceded the position of CDU/CSU's joint candidate for the chancellor's office to the leader of the sister party, Bavarian minister-president Edmund Stoiber.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] CDU and CSU polled slightly higher (29.5% and 9.0%, respectively), but still lacked the majority needed for a CDU–FDP coalition government and stayed in opposition.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] In 2005, early elections were called after the CDU dealt the governing SPD a major blow, winning more than ten state elections, most of which were landslide victories.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The resulting grand coalition between the CDU/CSU and the SPD faced a serious challenge stemming from both parties' demand for the chancellorship.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] After three weeks of negotiations, the two parties reached a deal whereby CDU received the chancellorship while the SPD retained 8 of the 16 seats in the cabinet and a majority of the most prestigious cabinet posts.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The coalition deal was approved by both parties at party conferences on 14 November.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Merkel was confirmed as the first female Chancellor of Germany by the majority of delegates (397 to 217) in the newly assembled Bundestag on 22 November.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Since her first term in office, from 2005 to 2009, there have been discussions if the CDU was still "sufficiently conservative" or if it was "social-democratising".
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Although the CDU/CSU lost support in the 2009 federal elections, their "desired partner" the FDP experienced the best election cycle in its history, thereby enabling a CDU/CSU–FDP coalition.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] This marked the first change of coalition partner by a Chancellor in German history and the first centre-right coalition government since 1998.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The decisions to suspend conscription (late 2010) and to phase out nuclear energy (shortly after the Fukushima disaster in 2011) broke with long-term principles of the CDU, moving the party into a more socially liberal direction and alienating some of its more conservative members and voters.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] At its November 2011 conference the party proposed a "wage floor", after having expressly rejected minimum wages during the previous years.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Some of the promises in the CDU's 2013 election platform were seen as "overtaking the SPD on the left".
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] While this strategy proved to be quite successful in elections, it also raised warnings that the CDU's profile would become "random", the party would lose its "essence" and it might even be dangerous for democracy in general if parties became indistinguishable and voters demotivated.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] President Wulff resigned in February 2012 due to allegations of corruption, triggering an early presidential election.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] This time the CDU supported, reluctantly, nonpartisan candidate Joachim Gauck.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CDU/CSU–FDP coalition lasted until the 2013 federal election, when the FDP lost all its seats in the Bundestag while the CDU and CSU won their best result since 1990, only a few seats short of an absolute majority.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] This was partly due to the CDU's expansion of voter base to all socio-structural groups (class, age or gender), partly due to the personal popularity of Chancellor Merkel.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] After talks with the Greens had failed, the CDU/CSU formed a new grand coalition with the SPD.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Despite their long-cherished slogan of "There must be no democratically legitimised party to the right of CDU/CSU", the Union has had a serious competitor to its right since 2013.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The right-wing populist Alternative for Germany (AfD) was founded with the involvement of disgruntled CDU members.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] It drew on the discontent of some conservatives with the Merkel administration's handling of the European debt crisis (2009–14) and later the 2015 refugee crisis, lamenting a purported loss of sovereignty and control or even "state failure".
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Nearly 10 percent of early AfD members were defectors from the CDU.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] In 2017, the Bundestag voted to legalise same-sex marriage.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Merkel had allowed the conscience vote to happen despite her personal objections.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] While she herself and the majority of the party's representatives voted against the proposal, a number of CDU deputies supported it.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] In the 2017 election, the CDU and CSU lost a large portion of their vote share: With 26.8 percent of party list votes, the CDU received its worst result since 1949, losing more than fifty seats in the Bundestag (despite an enlargement of the parliament).
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] After failing to negotiate a coalition with the FDP and Greens, they continued their grand coalition with the SPD.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] In October 2018, Merkel announced that she would step down as leader of the CDU that December and not seek reelection, but wanted to remain as Chancellor until 2021.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] On 7 December 2018, Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer was elected as federal chairwoman of the CDU.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Kramp-Karrenbauer was considered Merkel's ideological successor, though holding more socially conservative positions, such as opposition to same-sex marriage.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Kramp-Karrenbauer's election saw a rise in support for the CDU in national polling, and her personal popularity was initially high.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] However, she suffered a sharp decline in popularity in the lead-up to the 2019 European Parliament election, in which the CDU/CSU suffered its worst ever result in a national election with just 29%.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Kramp-Karrenbauer thereafter remained one of the least popular politicians nationally.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CSU's Manfred Weber was the *Spitzenkandidat* for the European People's Party in the 2019 European Parliament election.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] However, the EPP group ultimately nominated the CDU's Ursula von der Leyen as their candidate for President of the European Commission; she was elected in July 2019, becoming the first woman to hold the office.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Kramp-Karrenbauer resigned as party chair on 10 February 2020, in the midst of the 2020 Thuringian government crisis.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The Thuringian CDU had been perceived as cooperating with the Alternative for Germany (AfD) to prevent the election of a left-wing government, breaching the long-standing taboo in Germany surrounding cooperation with the far-right.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Kramp-Karrenbauer was perceived as unable to enforce discipline within the party during the crisis, which she claimed was complicated by unclear positions within the party regarding cooperation with the AfD and The Left, which party statute holds to be equally unacceptable.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] While the Thuringia crisis was the immediate trigger for Kramp-Karrenbauer's resignation, she stated the decision had "matured some time ago", and media attributed it to the troubled development of her brief leadership.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Kramp-Karrenbauer remained in office as Minister of Defence and interim party leader from February until the leadership election was held in January 2021.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Originally scheduled for April 2020, it was delayed multiple times due to the COVID-19 pandemic, and was ultimately held online.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Minister-President of North Rhine-Westphalia Armin Laschet won the election with 52.8% of delegate votes.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] His main opponent Friedrich Merz, was seen as more right-wing, who won 47.2% of vote; Merz had also run against Kramp-Karrenbauer in 2018 and been defeated.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Laschet's election was seen as an affirmation of Merkel's leadership and the CDU's centrist orientation.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] On 7 October 2021, Armin Laschet, signaled that he would step down after a disastrous general election result, with the CDU suffering its worst ever general election result.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] A new leadership election was called in December and Friedrich Merz, of the right-wing faction of the CDU, was elected by a large majority of 62.1% of voters, defeating pro-Merkel candidates Norbert Röttgen and Helge Braun.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The Congress of the CDU officially elected Merz as new party Chairman on 22 January 2022, and he assumed office on 31 January 2022.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] In the 2024 European parliament election, the CDU remained the largest party in Germany, winning 30.0% of the vote in a combined list with the CSU, led by CSU MEP Manfred Weber.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The combined list held on to all 29 seats, with the CDU maintaining 23 seats while the CSU had the remaining 6 seats.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] In October 2024, CDU again became proponents of nuclear energy, advocating reactivation of closed reactors and construction of new plants.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CDU contested the 2025 German federal election with Friedrich Merz as their chancellor candidate.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Their manifesto signalled a shift to the right on immigration as well as increased support for Ukraine.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CDU eventually won the election, gaining 12 seats.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Following the election results, the CDU began negotiations with the SPD to form another grand coalition.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] In May 2025, Friedrich Merz, leader of the CDU, formed a coalition government between the CDU/CSU and the SPD (grand coalition).
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Co-leader of the SPD, Lars Klingbeil, became vice chancellor and finance minister of the new government.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] In her 2005 campaign, Angela Merkel was unwilling to express explicitly Christian views while maintaining that her party had never lost its concept of values.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Merkel and Bundestag President Norbert Lammert have been keen to clarify that CDU references to the "dominant culture" imply "tolerance and living together".
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] According to party analyst Stephan Eisel, her avoiding the values issue may have had the opposite effect as she failed to mobilize the party's core constituency.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CDU applies the principles of Christian democracy and emphasizes the "Christian understanding of humans and their responsibility toward God".
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] However, CDU membership consists of people adhering to a variety of religions as well as non-religious individuals.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CDU's policies derive from political Catholicism, Catholic social teaching and political Protestantism as well as economic liberalism and national conservatism.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The party has adopted more liberal economic policies since Helmut Kohl's term in office as the Chancellor of Germany (1982–1998).
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] As a conservative party, the CDU supports stronger punishments of crimes and involvement on the part of the Bundeswehr in cases of domestic anti-terrorism offensives.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] In terms of immigrants, the CDU supports initiatives to integrate immigrants through language courses and aims to further control immigration.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] It holds that dual citizenship should only be allowed in exceptional cases.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] In terms of foreign policy, the CDU commits itself to European integration and a strong relation with the United States.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] In the European Union, the party opposes the entry of Turkey, preferring instead a privileged partnership.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] In addition to citing various human rights violations, the CDU also believes that Turkey's unwillingness to recognise Cyprus as an independent sovereign state contradicts the European Union policy that its members must recognise the existence of one another.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The party supports a business-friendly adaptation of the European Green Deal, and would like to continue to allow vehicles with combustion engines, research synthetic fuels and promote research into nuclear fusion.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The party calls for EU member states to limit their annual borrowing to three percent of their gross domestic product.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CDU has governed in four federal-level and numerous state-level Grand Coalitions with the Social Democratic Party (SPD) as well as in state and local-level coalitions with the Alliance 90/The Greens.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CDU has an official party congress adjudication that prohibits coalitions and any sort of cooperation with either The Left or the Alternative for Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] CDU officially prohibits any cooperation with the AfD, but does not clearly define what that means.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] In the eastern federal states, however, there is ongoing tolerance for, or cooperation of CDU with, the right-wing radical AfD at the local and district level.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] CDU leader Friedrich Merz took blowback for his political approaches to the AfD after he called his party in 2023 an "alternative... with substance".
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Political observers from abroad say that the CDU's boundaries with the far-right are eroding.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The party congress is the highest organ of the CDU.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] It meets at least every two years, determines the basic lines of CDU policy, approves the party program and decides on the statutes of the CDU.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CDU party congress consists of the delegates of the CDU regional associations, the foreign associations and the honorary chairmen.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The state associations send exactly 1,000 delegates who have to be elected by the state or district conventions.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The number of delegates that a regional association can send depends on the number of members of the association six months before the party congress and the result of the last federal election in the respective federal state.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The foreign associations recognized by the federal executive committee each send a delegate to the party congress, regardless of their number of members.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The federal committee is the second highest body and deals with all political and organizational matters that are not expressly reserved for the federal party congress.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] For this reason it is often called a *small party congress*.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CDU federal executive heads the federal party.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] It implements the resolutions of the federal party congress and the federal committee and convenes the federal party congress.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CDU Presidium is responsible for executing the resolutions of the federal executive committee and handling current and urgent business.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] It consists of the leading members of the federal executive board and is not an organ of the CDU in Germany.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Before 1966, membership totals in the CDU organisation were only estimated.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The numbers after 1966 are based on the total from 31 December of the previous year.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The Konrad Adenauer Foundation is the think-tank of the CDU.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] It is named after the first Chancellor of the Federal Republic of Germany and first president of the CDU.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Its annual budget amounts to around 120 million euro and is mostly funded by taxpayer money.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Both the CDU and the Christian Social Union in Bavaria (CSU) originated after World War II, sharing a concern for the Christian worldview.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] In the Bundestag, the CDU is represented in a common faction with the CSU.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] This faction is called CDU/CSU, or informally the Union.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Its basis is a binding agreement known as a *Fraktionsvertrag* between the two parties.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CDU and CSU share a common youth organisation, the Junge Union, a common pupil organisation, the Schüler Union Deutschlands, a common student organisation, the Ring Christlich-Demokratischer Studenten and a common *Mittelstand* organisation, the Mittelstands- und Wirtschaftsvereinigung.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CDU and CSU are legally and organisationally separate parties; their ideological differences are sometimes a source of conflict.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The most notable and serious such incident was in 1976, when the CSU under Franz Josef Strauß ended the alliance with the CDU at a party conference in Wildbad Kreuth.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] This decision was reversed shortly thereafter when the CDU threatened to run candidates against the CSU in Bavaria.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] Since its formation, the CSU has been more conservative than the CDU.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CSU and the state of Bavaria decided not to sign the Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany as they insisted on more autonomy for the individual states.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CSU has actively participated in all political affairs of the Bundestag, the German government, the Bundesrat, the parliamentary elections of the German President, the European Parliament and meetings with Mikhail Gorbachev in Russia.
[src:alois-mertes/christian-democratic-union-of-germany] The CDU does not contest elections in Bavaria due to the alliance with Bavarian sister party, the Christian Social Union in Bavaria.
